188 void FunctionVarLocs::init(FunctionVarLocsBuilder &Builder) { 0
189 // Add the single-location variables first. ----
190 for (const auto &VarLoc : Builder.SingleLocVars) 0
191 VarLocRecords.emplace_back(VarLoc); 0
192 // Mark the end of the section. ----
193 SingleVarLocEnd = VarLocRecords.size(); 0
194 ----
195 // Insert a contiguous block of VarLocInfos for each instruction, mapping it ----
196 // to the start and end position in the vector with VarLocsBeforeInst. ----
197 for (auto &P : Builder.VarLocsBeforeInst) { 0
198 unsigned BlockStart = VarLocRecords.size(); 0
199 for (const VarLocInfo &VarLoc : P.second) 0
200 VarLocRecords.emplace_back(VarLoc); 0
201 unsigned BlockEnd = VarLocRecords.size(); 0
202 // Record the start and end indices. ----
203 if (BlockEnd != BlockStart) 0
204 VarLocsBeforeInst[P.first] = {BlockStart, BlockEnd}; 0
205 } ----
206 ----
207 // Copy the Variables vector from the builder's UniqueVector. ----
208 assert(Variables.empty() && "Expect clear before init"); 0
209 // UniqueVectors IDs are one-based (which means the VarLocInfo VarID values ----
210 // are one-based) so reserve an extra and insert a dummy. ----
211 Variables.reserve(Builder.Variables.size() + 1); 0
212 Variables.push_back(DebugVariable(nullptr, std::nullopt, nullptr)); 0
213 Variables.append(Builder.Variables.begin(), Builder.Variables.end()); 0
214 } 0

223 /// Walk backwards along constant GEPs and bitcasts to the base storage from \p ----
224 /// Start as far as possible. Prepend \Expression with the offset and append it ----
225 /// with a DW_OP_deref that haes been implicit until now. Returns the walked-to ----
226 /// value and modified expression. ----
227 static std::pair ----
228 walkToAllocaAndPrependOffsetDeref(const DataLayout &DL, Value *Start, 0
229 DIExpression *Expression) { ----
230 APInt OffsetInBytes(DL.getTypeSizeInBits(Start->getType()), false); 0
231 Value *End = ----
232 Start->stripAndAccumulateInBoundsConstantOffsets(DL, OffsetInBytes); 0
233 SmallVector Ops; 0
234 if (OffsetInBytes.getBoolValue()) { 0
235 Ops = {dwarf::DW_OP_plus_uconst, OffsetInBytes.getZExtValue()}; 0
236 Expression = DIExpression::prependOpcodes( 0
237 Expression, Ops, /*StackValue=*/false, /*EntryValue=*/false); ----
238 } ----
239 Expression = DIExpression::append(Expression, {dwarf::DW_OP_deref}); 0
240 return {End, Expression}; 0
241 } 0
242 ----
243 /// Extract the offset used in \p DIExpr. Returns std::nullopt if the expression ----
244 /// doesn't explicitly describe a memory location with DW_OP_deref or if the ----
245 /// expression is too complex to interpret. ----
246 static std::optional ----
247 getDerefOffsetInBytes(const DIExpression *DIExpr) { 0
248 int64_t Offset = 0; 0
249 const unsigned NumElements = DIExpr->getNumElements(); 0
250 const auto Elements = DIExpr->getElements(); 0
251 unsigned ExpectedDerefIdx = 0; 0
252 // Extract the offset. ----
253 if (NumElements > 2 && Elements[0] == dwarf::DW_OP_plus_uconst) { 0
254 Offset = Elements[1]; 0
255 ExpectedDerefIdx = 2; 0
256 } else if (NumElements > 3 && Elements[0] == dwarf::DW_OP_constu) { 0
257 ExpectedDerefIdx = 3; 0
258 if (Elements[2] == dwarf::DW_OP_plus) 0
259 Offset = Elements[1]; 0
260 else if (Elements[2] == dwarf::DW_OP_minus) 0
261 Offset = -Elements[1]; 0
262 else ----
263 return std::nullopt; 0
264 } ----
265 ----
266 // If that's all there is it means there's no deref. ----
267 if (ExpectedDerefIdx >= NumElements) 0
268 return std::nullopt; 0
269 ----
270 // Check the next element is DW_OP_deref - otherwise this is too complex or ----
271 // isn't a deref expression. ----
272 if (Elements[ExpectedDerefIdx] != dwarf::DW_OP_deref) 0
273 return std::nullopt; 0
274 ----
275 // Check the final operation is either the DW_OP_deref or is a fragment. ----
276 if (NumElements == ExpectedDerefIdx + 1) 0
277 return Offset; // Ends with deref. 0
278 unsigned ExpectedFragFirstIdx = ExpectedDerefIdx + 1; 0
279 unsigned ExpectedFragFinalIdx = ExpectedFragFirstIdx + 2; 0
280 if (NumElements == ExpectedFragFinalIdx + 1 && 0
281 Elements[ExpectedFragFirstIdx] == dwarf::DW_OP_LLVM_fragment) 0
282 return Offset; // Ends with deref + fragment. 0
283 ----
284 // Don't bother trying to interpret anything more complex. ----
285 return std::nullopt; 0
286 } ----

299 // referencing is enabled. However, it may cause LiveDebugVariables to create ----
300 // incorrect locations. Since instruction-referencing mode effectively ----
301 // bypasses LiveDebugVariables we only enable coalescing if the cl::opt flag ----
302 // has not been explicitly set and instruction-referencing is turned on. ----
303 switch (CoalesceAdjacentFragmentsOpt) { 0

305 return debuginfoShouldUseDebugInstrRef( 0
306 Triple(F.getParent()->getTargetTriple())); 0
307 case cl::boolOrDefault::BOU_TRUE: 0
308 return true; 0
309 case cl::boolOrDefault::BOU_FALSE: 0

315 namespace { ----
316 /// In dwarf emission, the following sequence ----
317 /// 1. dbg.value ... Fragment(0, 64) ----
318 /// 2. dbg.value ... Fragment(0, 32) ----
319 /// effectively sets Fragment(32, 32) to undef (each def sets all bits not in ----
320 /// the intersection of the fragments to having "no location"). This makes ----
321 /// sense for implicit location values because splitting the computed values ----
322 /// could be troublesome, and is probably quite uncommon. When we convert ----
323 /// dbg.assigns to dbg.value+deref this kind of thing is common, and describing ----
324 /// a location (memory) rather than a value means we don't need to worry about ----
325 /// splitting any values, so we try to recover the rest of the fragment ----
326 /// location here. ----
327 /// This class performs a(nother) dataflow analysis over the function, adding ----
328 /// variable locations so that any bits of a variable with a memory location ----
329 /// have that location explicitly reinstated at each subsequent variable ----
330 /// location definition that that doesn't overwrite those bits. i.e. after a ----
331 /// variable location def, insert new defs for the memory location with ----
332 /// fragments for the difference of "all bits currently in memory" and "the ----
333 /// fragment of the second def". ----
334 class MemLocFragmentFill { ----
335 Function &Fn; ----
336 FunctionVarLocsBuilder *FnVarLocs; ----
337 const DenseSet *VarsWithStackSlot; ----
338 bool CoalesceAdjacentFragments; ----
339 ----
340 // 0 = no memory location. ----
341 using BaseAddress = unsigned; ----
342 using OffsetInBitsTy = unsigned; ----
343 using FragTraits = IntervalMapHalfOpenInfo; ----
344 using FragsInMemMap = IntervalMap< ----
345 OffsetInBitsTy, BaseAddress, ----
346 IntervalMapImpl::NodeSizer::LeafSize, ----
347 FragTraits>; ----
348 FragsInMemMap::Allocator IntervalMapAlloc; ----
349 using VarFragMap = DenseMap; ----
350 ----
351 /// IDs for memory location base addresses in maps. Use 0 to indicate that ----
352 /// there's no memory location. ----

367 /// BBInsertBeforeMap holds a description for the set of location defs to be ----
368 /// inserted after the analysis is complete. It is updated during the dataflow ----
369 /// and the entry for a block is CLEARED each time it is (re-)visited. After ----
370 /// the dataflow is complete, each block entry will contain the set of defs ----
371 /// calculated during the final (fixed-point) iteration. ----

374 static bool intervalMapsAreEqual(const FragsInMemMap &A, 0
375 const FragsInMemMap &B) { ----
376 auto AIt = A.begin(), AEnd = A.end(); 0
377 auto BIt = B.begin(), BEnd = B.end(); 0
378 for (; AIt != AEnd; ++AIt, ++BIt) { 0
379 if (BIt == BEnd) 0
380 return false; // B has fewer elements than A. 0
381 if (AIt.start() != BIt.start() || AIt.stop() != BIt.stop()) 0
382 return false; // Interval is different. 0
383 if (*AIt != *BIt) 0
384 return false; // Value at interval is different. 0
385 } ----
386 // AIt == AEnd. Check BIt is also now at end. ----
387 return BIt == BEnd; 0
388 } 0
389 ----
390 static bool varFragMapsAreEqual(const VarFragMap &A, const VarFragMap &B) { 0
391 if (A.size() != B.size()) 0
392 return false; 0
393 for (const auto &APair : A) { 0
394 auto BIt = B.find(APair.first); 0
395 if (BIt == B.end()) 0
396 return false; 0
397 if (!intervalMapsAreEqual(APair.second, BIt->second)) 0
398 return false; 0
399 } ----
400 return true; 0
401 } ----

412 std::string toString(FragsInMemMap::const_iterator It, bool Newline = true) { 0

414 std::stringstream S(String); 0
415 if (It.valid()) { 0

417 << "): " << toString(It.value()); 0
418 } else { ----

426 FragsInMemMap meetFragments(const FragsInMemMap &A, const FragsInMemMap &B) { 0
427 FragsInMemMap Result(IntervalMapAlloc); 0
428 for (auto AIt = A.begin(), AEnd = A.end(); AIt != AEnd; ++AIt) { 0
429 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "a " << toString(AIt)); 0
430 // This is basically copied from process() and inverted (process is ----
431 // performing something like a union whereas this is more of an ----
432 // intersect). ----
433 ----
434 // There's no work to do if interval `a` overlaps no fragments in map `B`. ----
435 if (!B.overlaps(AIt.start(), AIt.stop())) 0
436 continue; 0
437 ----
438 // Does StartBit intersect an existing fragment? ----
439 auto FirstOverlap = B.find(AIt.start()); 0
440 assert(FirstOverlap != B.end()); 0
441 bool IntersectStart = FirstOverlap.start() < AIt.start(); 0
442 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "- FirstOverlap " << toString(FirstOverlap, false) 0
443 << ", IntersectStart: " << IntersectStart << "\n"); ----
444 ----
445 // Does EndBit intersect an existing fragment? ----
446 auto LastOverlap = B.find(AIt.stop()); 0
447 bool IntersectEnd = ----
448 LastOverlap != B.end() && LastOverlap.start() < AIt.stop(); 0
449 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "- LastOverlap " << toString(LastOverlap, false) 0
450 << ", IntersectEnd: " << IntersectEnd << "\n"); ----
451 ----
452 // Check if both ends of `a` intersect the same interval `b`. ----
453 if (IntersectStart && IntersectEnd && FirstOverlap == LastOverlap) { 0
454 // Insert `a` (`a` is contained in `b`) if the values match. ----
455 // [ a ] ----
456 // [ - b - ] ----
457 // - ----
458 // [ r ] ----
459 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "- a is contained within " 0
460 << toString(FirstOverlap)); ----
461 if (*AIt && *AIt == *FirstOverlap) 0
462 Result.insert(AIt.start(), AIt.stop(), *AIt); 0
463 } else { ----
464 // There's an overlap but `a` is not fully contained within ----
465 // `b`. Shorten any end-point intersections. ----
466 // [ - a - ] ----
467 // [ - b - ] ----
468 // - ----
469 // [ r ] ----
470 auto Next = FirstOverlap; 0
471 if (IntersectStart) { 0
472 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "- insert intersection of a and " 0
473 << toString(FirstOverlap)); ----
474 if (*AIt && *AIt == *FirstOverlap) 0
475 Result.insert(AIt.start(), FirstOverlap.stop(), *AIt); 0
476 ++Next; 0
477 } ----
478 // [ - a - ] ----
479 // [ - b - ] ----
480 // - ----
481 // [ r ] ----
482 if (IntersectEnd) { 0
483 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "- insert intersection of a and " 0
484 << toString(LastOverlap)); ----
485 if (*AIt && *AIt == *LastOverlap) 0
486 Result.insert(LastOverlap.start(), AIt.stop(), *AIt); 0
487 } ----
488 ----
489 // Insert all intervals in map `B` that are contained within interval ----
490 // `a` where the values match. ----
491 // [ - - a - - ] ----
492 // [ b1 ] [ b2 ] ----
493 // - ----
494 // [ r1 ] [ r2 ] ----
495 while (Next != B.end() && Next.start() < AIt.stop() && 0
496 Next.stop() <= AIt.stop()) { 0
497 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() 0
498 << "- insert intersection of a and " << toString(Next)); ----
499 if (*AIt && *AIt == *Next) 0
500 Result.insert(Next.start(), Next.stop(), *Next); 0
501 ++Next; 0
502 } ----
503 } 0
504 } 0
505 return Result; 0
506 } ----

508 /// Meet \p A and \p B, storing the result in \p A. ----
509 void meetVars(VarFragMap &A, const VarFragMap &B) { 0
510 // Meet A and B. ----
511 // ----
512 // Result = meet(a, b) for a in A, b in B where Var(a) == Var(b) ----
513 for (auto It = A.begin(), End = A.end(); It != End; ++It) { 0
514 unsigned AVar = It->first; 0
515 FragsInMemMap &AFrags = It->second; 0
516 auto BIt = B.find(AVar); 0
517 if (BIt == B.end()) { 0
518 A.erase(It); 0
519 continue; // Var has no bits defined in B. 0
520 } ----
521 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "meet fragment maps for " 0
522 << Aggregates[AVar].first->getName() << "\n"); ----
523 AFrags = meetFragments(AFrags, BIt->second); 0
524 } ----
525 } 0
526 ----
527 bool meet(const BasicBlock &BB, 0
528 const SmallPtrSet &Visited) { ----
529 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "meet block info from preds of " << BB.getName() 0
530 << "\n"); ----
531 ----
532 VarFragMap BBLiveIn; 0
533 bool FirstMeet = true; 0
534 // LiveIn locs for BB is the meet of the already-processed preds' LiveOut ----
535 // locs. ----
536 for (auto I = pred_begin(&BB), E = pred_end(&BB); I != E; I++) { 0
537 // Ignore preds that haven't been processed yet. This is essentially the ----
538 // same as initialising all variables to implicit top value () which is ----
539 // the identity value for the meet operation. ----
540 const BasicBlock *Pred = *I; 0
541 if (!Visited.count(Pred)) 0
542 continue; 0
543 ----
544 auto PredLiveOut = LiveOut.find(Pred); 0
545 assert(PredLiveOut != LiveOut.end()); 0
546 ----
547 if (FirstMeet) { 0
548 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "BBLiveIn = " << Pred->getName() << "\n"); 0
549 BBLiveIn = PredLiveOut->second; 0
550 FirstMeet = false; 0
551 } else { ----
552 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "BBLiveIn = meet BBLiveIn, " << Pred->getName() 0
553 << "\n"); ----
554 meetVars(BBLiveIn, PredLiveOut->second); 0
555 } ----
556 ----
557 // An empty set is for the intersect-like meet operation. If we've ----
558 // already got there's no need to run the code - we know the result is ----
559 // since `meet(a, ) = `. ----
560 if (BBLiveIn.size() == 0) 0
561 break; 0
562 } ----
563 ----
564 auto CurrentLiveInEntry = LiveIn.find(&BB); 0
565 // If there's no LiveIn entry for the block yet, add it. ----
566 if (CurrentLiveInEntry == LiveIn.end()) { 0
567 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "change=true (first) on meet on " << BB.getName() 0
568 << "\n"); ----
569 LiveIn[&BB] = std::move(BBLiveIn); 0
570 return /*Changed=*/true; 0
571 } ----
572 ----
573 // If the LiveIn set has changed (expensive check) update it and return ----
574 // true. ----
575 if (!varFragMapsAreEqual(BBLiveIn, CurrentLiveInEntry->second)) { 0
576 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "change=true on meet on " << BB.getName() << "\n"); 0
577 CurrentLiveInEntry->second = std::move(BBLiveIn); 0
578 return /*Changed=*/true; 0
579 } ----
580 ----
581 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "change=false on meet on " << BB.getName() << "\n"); 0
582 return /*Changed=*/false; 0
583 } 0
584 ----
585 void insertMemLoc(BasicBlock &BB, Instruction &Before, unsigned Var, 0
586 unsigned StartBit, unsigned EndBit, unsigned Base, ----
587 DebugLoc DL) { ----
588 assert(StartBit < EndBit && "Cannot create fragment of size <= 0"); 0
589 if (!Base) 0
590 return; 0
591 FragMemLoc Loc; 0
592 Loc.Var = Var; 0
593 Loc.OffsetInBits = StartBit; 0
594 Loc.SizeInBits = EndBit - StartBit; 0
595 assert(Base && "Expected a non-zero ID for Base address"); 0
596 Loc.Base = Base; 0
597 Loc.DL = DL; 0
598 BBInsertBeforeMap[&BB][&Before].push_back(Loc); 0
599 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Add mem def for " << Aggregates[Var].first->getName() 0
600 << " bits [" << StartBit << ", " << EndBit << ")\n"); ----
601 } 0
602 ----
603 /// Inserts a new dbg def if the interval found when looking up \p StartBit ----
604 /// in \p FragMap starts before \p StartBit or ends after \p EndBit (which ----
605 /// indicates - assuming StartBit->EndBit has just been inserted - that the ----
606 /// slice has been coalesced in the map). ----
607 void coalesceFragments(BasicBlock &BB, Instruction &Before, unsigned Var, 0
608 unsigned StartBit, unsigned EndBit, unsigned Base, ----
609 DebugLoc DL, const FragsInMemMap &FragMap) { ----
610 if (!CoalesceAdjacentFragments) 0
611 return; 0
612 // We've inserted the location into the map. The map will have coalesced ----
613 // adjacent intervals (variable fragments) that describe the same memory ----
614 // location. Use this knowledge to insert a debug location that describes ----
615 // that coalesced fragment. This may eclipse other locs we've just ----
616 // inserted. This is okay as redundant locs will be cleaned up later. ----
617 auto CoalescedFrag = FragMap.find(StartBit); 0
618 // Bail if no coalescing has taken place. ----
619 if (CoalescedFrag.start() == StartBit && CoalescedFrag.stop() == EndBit) 0
620 return; 0
621 ----
622 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "- Insert loc for bits " << CoalescedFrag.start() 0
623 << " to " << CoalescedFrag.stop() << "\n"); ----
624 insertMemLoc(BB, Before, Var, CoalescedFrag.start(), CoalescedFrag.stop(), 0
625 Base, DL); ----
626 } 0
627 ----
628 void addDef(const VarLocInfo &VarLoc, Instruction &Before, BasicBlock &BB, 0
629 VarFragMap &LiveSet) { ----
630 DebugVariable DbgVar = FnVarLocs->getVariable(VarLoc.VariableID); 0
631 if (skipVariable(DbgVar.getVariable())) 0
632 return; 0
633 // Don't bother doing anything for this variables if we know it's fully ----
634 // promoted. We're only interested in variables that (sometimes) live on ----
635 // the stack here. ----
636 if (!VarsWithStackSlot->count(getAggregate(DbgVar))) 0
637 return; 0
638 unsigned Var = Aggregates.insert( 0
639 DebugAggregate(DbgVar.getVariable(), VarLoc.DL.getInlinedAt())); 0
640 ----
641 // [StartBit: EndBit) are the bits affected by this def. ----
642 const DIExpression *DIExpr = VarLoc.Expr; 0
643 unsigned StartBit; ----
644 unsigned EndBit; ----
645 if (auto Frag = DIExpr->getFragmentInfo()) { 0
646 StartBit = Frag->OffsetInBits; 0
647 EndBit = StartBit + Frag->SizeInBits; 0
648 } else { ----
649 assert(static_cast(DbgVar.getVariable()->getSizeInBits())); 0
650 StartBit = 0; 0
651 EndBit = *DbgVar.getVariable()->getSizeInBits(); 0
652 } ----
653 ----
654 // We will only fill fragments for simple memory-describing dbg.value ----
655 // intrinsics. If the fragment offset is the same as the offset from the ----
656 // base pointer, do The Thing, otherwise fall back to normal dbg.value ----
657 // behaviour. AssignmentTrackingLowering has generated DIExpressions ----
658 // written in terms of the base pointer. ----
659 // TODO: Remove this condition since the fragment offset doesn't always ----
660 // equal the offset from base pointer (e.g. for a SROA-split variable). ----
661 const auto DerefOffsetInBytes = getDerefOffsetInBytes(DIExpr); 0
662 const unsigned Base = ----
663 DerefOffsetInBytes && *DerefOffsetInBytes * 8 == StartBit 0
664 ? Bases.insert(VarLoc.Values) 0
665 : 0; 0
666 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "DEF " << DbgVar.getVariable()->getName() << " [" 0
667 << StartBit << ", " << EndBit << "): " << toString(Base) ----
668 << "\n"); ----
669 ----
670 // First of all, any locs that use mem that are disrupted need reinstating. ----
671 // Unfortunately, IntervalMap doesn't let us insert intervals that overlap ----
672 // with existing intervals so this code involves a lot of fiddling around ----
673 // with intervals to do that manually. ----
674 auto FragIt = LiveSet.find(Var); 0
675 ----
676 // Check if the variable does not exist in the map. ----
677 if (FragIt == LiveSet.end()) { 0
678 // Add this variable to the BB map. ----
679 auto P = LiveSet.try_emplace(Var, FragsInMemMap(IntervalMapAlloc)); 0
680 assert(P.second && "Var already in map?"); 0
681 // Add the interval to the fragment map. ----
682 P.first->second.insert(StartBit, EndBit, Base); 0
683 return; 0
684 } ----
685 // The variable has an entry in the map. ----
686 ----
687 FragsInMemMap &FragMap = FragIt->second; 0
688 // First check the easy case: the new fragment `f` doesn't overlap with any ----
689 // intervals. ----
690 if (!FragMap.overlaps(StartBit, EndBit)) { 0
691 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "- No overlaps\n"); 0
692 FragMap.insert(StartBit, EndBit, Base); 0
693 coalesceFragments(BB, Before, Var, StartBit, EndBit, Base, VarLoc.DL, 0
694 FragMap); ----
695 return; 0
696 } ----
697 // There is at least one overlap. ----
698 ----
699 // Does StartBit intersect an existing fragment? ----
700 auto FirstOverlap = FragMap.find(StartBit); 0
701 assert(FirstOverlap != FragMap.end()); 0
702 bool IntersectStart = FirstOverlap.start() < StartBit; 0
703 ----
704 // Does EndBit intersect an existing fragment? ----
705 auto LastOverlap = FragMap.find(EndBit); 0
706 bool IntersectEnd = LastOverlap.valid() && LastOverlap.start() < EndBit; 0
707 ----
708 // Check if both ends of `f` intersect the same interval `i`. ----
709 if (IntersectStart && IntersectEnd && FirstOverlap == LastOverlap) { 0
710 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "- Intersect single interval @ both ends\n"); 0
711 // Shorten `i` so that there's space to insert `f`. ----
712 // [ f ] ----
713 // [ - i - ] ----
714 // + ----
715 // [ i ][ f ][ i ] ----
716 ----
717 // Save values for use after inserting a new interval. ----
718 auto EndBitOfOverlap = FirstOverlap.stop(); 0
719 unsigned OverlapValue = FirstOverlap.value(); 0
720 ----
721 // Shorten the overlapping interval. ----
722 FirstOverlap.setStop(StartBit); 0
723 insertMemLoc(BB, Before, Var, FirstOverlap.start(), StartBit, 0
724 OverlapValue, VarLoc.DL); 0
725 ----
726 // Insert a new interval to represent the end part. ----
727 FragMap.insert(EndBit, EndBitOfOverlap, OverlapValue); 0
728 insertMemLoc(BB, Before, Var, EndBit, EndBitOfOverlap, OverlapValue, 0
729 VarLoc.DL); 0
730 ----
731 // Insert the new (middle) fragment now there is space. ----
732 FragMap.insert(StartBit, EndBit, Base); 0
733 } else { ----
734 // There's an overlap but `f` may not be fully contained within ----
735 // `i`. Shorten any end-point intersections so that we can then ----
736 // insert `f`. ----
737 // [ - f - ] ----
738 // [ - i - ] ----
739 // | | ----
740 // [ i ] ----
741 // Shorten any end-point intersections. ----
742 if (IntersectStart) { 0
743 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "- Intersect interval at start\n"); 0
744 // Split off at the intersection. ----
745 FirstOverlap.setStop(StartBit); 0
746 insertMemLoc(BB, Before, Var, FirstOverlap.start(), StartBit, 0
747 *FirstOverlap, VarLoc.DL); 0
748 } ----
749 // [ - f - ] ----
750 // [ - i - ] ----
751 // | | ----
752 // [ i ] ----
753 if (IntersectEnd) { 0
754 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "- Intersect interval at end\n"); 0
755 // Split off at the intersection. ----
756 LastOverlap.setStart(EndBit); 0
757 insertMemLoc(BB, Before, Var, EndBit, LastOverlap.stop(), *LastOverlap, 0
758 VarLoc.DL); 0
759 } ----
760 ----
761 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "- Erase intervals contained within\n"); 0
762 // FirstOverlap and LastOverlap have been shortened such that they're ----
763 // no longer overlapping with [StartBit, EndBit). Delete any overlaps ----
764 // that remain (these will be fully contained within `f`). ----
765 // [ - f - ] } ----
766 // [ - i - ] } Intersection shortening that has happened above. ----
767 // | | } ----
768 // [ i ] } ----
769 // ----------------- ----
770 // [i2 ] } Intervals fully contained within `f` get erased. ----
771 // ----------------- ----
772 // [ - f - ][ i ] } Completed insertion. ----
773 auto It = FirstOverlap; 0
774 if (IntersectStart) 0
775 ++It; // IntersectStart: first overlap has been shortened. 0
776 while (It.valid() && It.start() >= StartBit && It.stop() <= EndBit) { 0
777 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "- Erase " << toString(It)); 0
778 It.erase(); // This increments It after removing the interval. 0
779 } ----
780 // We've dealt with all the overlaps now! ----
781 assert(!FragMap.overlaps(StartBit, EndBit)); 0
782 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "- Insert DEF into now-empty space\n"); 0
783 FragMap.insert(StartBit, EndBit, Base); 0
784 } 0
785 ----
786 coalesceFragments(BB, Before, Var, StartBit, EndBit, Base, VarLoc.DL, 0
787 FragMap); ----
788 } 0
789 ----
790 bool skipVariable(const DILocalVariable *V) { return !V->getSizeInBits(); } 0
791 ----
792 void process(BasicBlock &BB, VarFragMap &LiveSet) { 0
793 BBInsertBeforeMap[&BB].clear(); 0
794 for (auto &I : BB) { 0
795 if (const auto *Locs = FnVarLocs->getWedge(&I)) { 0
796 for (const VarLocInfo &Loc : *Locs) { 0
797 addDef(Loc, I, *I.getParent(), LiveSet); 0
798 } ----
799 } ----
800 } ----
801 } 0
802 ----
803 public: ----
804 MemLocFragmentFill(Function &Fn, 0
805 const DenseSet *VarsWithStackSlot, ----
806 bool CoalesceAdjacentFragments) ----
807 : Fn(Fn), VarsWithStackSlot(VarsWithStackSlot), 0
808 CoalesceAdjacentFragments(CoalesceAdjacentFragments) {} 0
809 ----
810 /// Add variable locations to \p FnVarLocs so that any bits of a variable ----
811 /// with a memory location have that location explicitly reinstated at each ----
812 /// subsequent variable location definition that that doesn't overwrite those ----
813 /// bits. i.e. after a variable location def, insert new defs for the memory ----
814 /// location with fragments for the difference of "all bits currently in ----
815 /// memory" and "the fragment of the second def". e.g. ----
816 /// ----
817 /// Before: ----
818 /// ----
819 /// var x bits 0 to 63: value in memory ----
820 /// more instructions ----
821 /// var x bits 0 to 31: value is %0 ----
822 /// ----
823 /// After: ----
824 /// ----
825 /// var x bits 0 to 63: value in memory ----
826 /// more instructions ----
827 /// var x bits 0 to 31: value is %0 ----
828 /// var x bits 32 to 61: value in memory ; <-- new loc def ----
829 /// ----
830 void run(FunctionVarLocsBuilder *FnVarLocs) { 0
831 if (!EnableMemLocFragFill) 0
832 return; 0
833 ----
834 this->FnVarLocs = FnVarLocs; 0
835 ----
836 // Prepare for traversal. ----
837 // ----
838 ReversePostOrderTraversal RPOT(&Fn); 0
839 std::priority_queue, ----
840 std::greater> ----
841 Worklist; 0
842 std::priority_queue, ----
843 std::greater> ----
844 Pending; 0
845 DenseMap OrderToBB; 0
846 DenseMap BBToOrder; 0
847 { // Init OrderToBB and BBToOrder. ----
848 unsigned int RPONumber = 0; 0
849 for (auto RI = RPOT.begin(), RE = RPOT.end(); RI != RE; ++RI) { 0
850 OrderToBB[RPONumber] = *RI; 0
851 BBToOrder[*RI] = RPONumber; 0
852 Worklist.push(RPONumber); 0
853 ++RPONumber; 0
854 } ----
855 LiveIn.init(RPONumber); 0
856 LiveOut.init(RPONumber); 0
857 } ----
858 ----
859 // Perform the traversal. ----
860 // ----
861 // This is a standard "intersect of predecessor outs" dataflow problem. To ----
862 // solve it, we perform meet() and process() using the two worklist method ----
863 // until the LiveIn data for each block becomes unchanging. ----
864 // ----
865 // This dataflow is essentially working on maps of sets and at each meet we ----
866 // intersect the maps and the mapped sets. So, initialized live-in maps ----
867 // monotonically decrease in value throughout the dataflow. ----
868 SmallPtrSet Visited; 0
869 while (!Worklist.empty() || !Pending.empty()) { 0
870 // We track what is on the pending worklist to avoid inserting the same ----
871 // thing twice. We could avoid this with a custom priority queue, but ----
872 // this is probably not worth it. ----
873 SmallPtrSet OnPending; 0
874 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Processing Worklist\n"); 0
875 while (!Worklist.empty()) { 0
876 BasicBlock *BB = OrderToBB[Worklist.top()]; 0
877 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\nPop BB " << BB->getName() << "\n"); 0
878 Worklist.pop(); 0
879 bool InChanged = meet(*BB, Visited); 0
880 // Always consider LiveIn changed on the first visit. ----
881 InChanged |= Visited.insert(BB).second; 0
882 if (InChanged) { 0
883 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() 0
884 << BB->getName() << " has new InLocs, process it\n"); ----
885 // Mutate a copy of LiveIn while processing BB. Once we've processed ----
886 // the terminator LiveSet is the LiveOut set for BB. ----
887 // This is an expensive copy! ----
888 VarFragMap LiveSet = LiveIn[BB]; 0
889 ----
890 // Process the instructions in the block. ----
891 process(*BB, LiveSet); 0
892 ----
893 // Relatively expensive check: has anything changed in LiveOut for BB? ----
894 if (!varFragMapsAreEqual(LiveOut[BB], LiveSet)) { 0
895 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << BB->getName() 0
896 << " has new OutLocs, add succs to worklist: [ "); ----
897 LiveOut[BB] = std::move(LiveSet); 0
898 for (auto I = succ_begin(BB), E = succ_end(BB); I != E; I++) { 0
899 if (OnPending.insert(*I).second) { 0
900 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << I->getName() << " "); 0
901 Pending.push(BBToOrder[*I]); 0
902 } ----
903 } ----
904 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "]\n"); 0
905 } ----
906 } 0
907 } ----
908 Worklist.swap(Pending); 0
909 // At this point, pending must be empty, since it was just the empty ----
910 // worklist ----
911 assert(Pending.empty() && "Pending should be empty"); 0
912 } 0
913 ----
914 // Insert new location defs. ----
915 for (auto &Pair : BBInsertBeforeMap) { 0
916 InsertMap &Map = Pair.second; 0
917 for (auto &Pair : Map) { 0
918 Instruction *InsertBefore = Pair.first; 0
919 assert(InsertBefore && "should never be null"); 0
920 auto FragMemLocs = Pair.second; 0
921 auto &Ctx = Fn.getContext(); 0
922 ----
923 for (auto &FragMemLoc : FragMemLocs) { 0
924 DIExpression *Expr = DIExpression::get(Ctx, std::nullopt); 0
925 if (FragMemLoc.SizeInBits != 0
926 *Aggregates[FragMemLoc.Var].first->getSizeInBits()) 0
927 Expr = *DIExpression::createFragmentExpression( 0
928 Expr, FragMemLoc.OffsetInBits, FragMemLoc.SizeInBits); 0
929 Expr = DIExpression::prepend(Expr, DIExpression::DerefAfter, 0
930 FragMemLoc.OffsetInBits / 8); 0
931 DebugVariable Var(Aggregates[FragMemLoc.Var].first, Expr, 0
932 FragMemLoc.DL.getInlinedAt()); 0
933 FnVarLocs->addVarLoc(InsertBefore, Var, Expr, FragMemLoc.DL, 0
934 Bases[FragMemLoc.Base]); 0
935 } ----
936 } 0
937 } ----
938 } 0
939 }; ----
940 ----
941 /// AssignmentTrackingLowering encapsulates a dataflow analysis over a function ----
942 /// that interprets assignment tracking debug info metadata and stores in IR to ----
943 /// create a map of variable locations. ----
944 class AssignmentTrackingLowering { ----
945 public: ----
946 /// The kind of location in use for a variable, where Mem is the stack home, ----
947 /// Val is an SSA value or const, and None means that there is not one single ----
948 /// kind (either because there are multiple or because there is none; it may ----
949 /// prove useful to split this into two values in the future). ----
950 /// ----
951 /// LocKind is a join-semilattice with the partial order: ----
952 /// None > Mem, Val ----
953 /// ----
954 /// i.e. ----
955 /// join(Mem, Mem) = Mem ----
956 /// join(Val, Val) = Val ----
957 /// join(Mem, Val) = None ----
958 /// join(None, Mem) = None ----
959 /// join(None, Val) = None ----
960 /// join(None, None) = None ----
961 /// ----
962 /// Note: the order is not `None > Val > Mem` because we're using DIAssignID ----
963 /// to name assignments and are not tracking the actual stored values. ----
964 /// Therefore currently there's no way to ensure that Mem values and Val ----
965 /// values are the same. This could be a future extension, though it's not ----
966 /// clear that many additional locations would be recovered that way in ----
967 /// practice as the likelihood of this sitation arising naturally seems ----
968 /// incredibly low. ----
969 enum class LocKind { Mem, Val, None }; ----
970 ----
971 /// An abstraction of the assignment of a value to a variable or memory ----
972 /// location. ----
973 /// ----
974 /// An Assignment is Known or NoneOrPhi. A Known Assignment means we have a ----
975 /// DIAssignID ptr that represents it. NoneOrPhi means that we don't (or ----
976 /// can't) know the ID of the last assignment that took place. ----
977 /// ----
978 /// The Status of the Assignment (Known or NoneOrPhi) is another ----
979 /// join-semilattice. The partial order is: ----
980 /// NoneOrPhi > Known {id_0, id_1, ...id_N} ----
981 /// ----
982 /// i.e. for all values x and y where x != y: ----
983 /// join(x, x) = x ----
984 /// join(x, y) = NoneOrPhi ----
985 struct Assignment { ----
986 enum S { Known, NoneOrPhi } Status; ----
987 /// ID of the assignment. nullptr if Status is not Known. ----
988 DIAssignID *ID; ----
989 /// The dbg.assign that marks this dbg-def. Mem-defs don't use this field. ----
990 /// May be nullptr. ----
991 DbgAssignIntrinsic *Source; ----
992 ----
993 bool isSameSourceAssignment(const Assignment &Other) const { 0
994 // Don't include Source in the equality check. Assignments are ----
995 // defined by their ID, not debug intrinsic(s). ----
996 return std::tie(Status, ID) == std::tie(Other.Status, Other.ID); 0
997 } ----
998 void dump(raw_ostream &OS) { 0
999 static const char *LUT[] = {"Known", "NoneOrPhi"}; ----
1000 OS << LUT[Status] << "(id="; 0
1001 if (ID) 0
1002 OS << ID; 0
1003 else ----
1004 OS << "null"; 0
1005 OS << ", s="; 0
1006 if (Source) 0
1007 OS << *Source; 0
1008 else ----
1009 OS << "null"; 0
1010 OS << ")"; 0
1011 } 0
1012 ----
1013 static Assignment make(DIAssignID *ID, DbgAssignIntrinsic *Source) { 0
1014 return Assignment(Known, ID, Source); 0
1015 } ----
1016 static Assignment makeFromMemDef(DIAssignID *ID) { 0
1017 return Assignment(Known, ID, nullptr); 0
1018 } ----
1019 static Assignment makeNoneOrPhi() { 0
1020 return Assignment(NoneOrPhi, nullptr, nullptr); 0
1021 } ----
1022 // Again, need a Top value? ----
1023 Assignment() ----
1024 : Status(NoneOrPhi), ID(nullptr), Source(nullptr) { ----
1025 } // Can we delete this? ----
1026 Assignment(S Status, DIAssignID *ID, DbgAssignIntrinsic *Source) 0
1027 : Status(Status), ID(ID), Source(Source) { 0
1028 // If the Status is Known then we expect there to be an assignment ID. ----
1029 assert(Status == NoneOrPhi || ID); 0
1030 } 0
1031 }; ----

1033 using AssignmentMap = SmallVector; ----
1034 using LocMap = SmallVector; ----
1035 using OverlapMap = DenseMap>; ----
1036 using UntaggedStoreAssignmentMap = ----
1037 DenseMap ----
1038 SmallVector>>; ----
1039 ----
1040 private: ----
1041 /// The highest numbered VariableID for partially promoted variables plus 1, ----
1042 /// the values for which start at 1. ----
1043 unsigned TrackedVariablesVectorSize = 0; ----
1044 /// Map a variable to the set of variables that it fully contains. ----
1045 OverlapMap VarContains; ----
1046 /// Map untagged stores to the variable fragments they assign to. Used by ----
1047 /// processUntaggedInstruction. ----
1048 UntaggedStoreAssignmentMap UntaggedStoreVars; ----
1049 ----
1050 // Machinery to defer inserting dbg.values. ----
1051 using InsertMap = MapVector>; ----
1052 InsertMap InsertBeforeMap; ----
1053 /// Clear the location definitions currently cached for insertion after /p ----
1054 /// After. ----
1055 void resetInsertionPoint(Instruction &After); ----
1056 void emitDbgValue(LocKind Kind, const DbgVariableIntrinsic *Source, ----
1057 Instruction *After); ----
1058 ----
1059 static bool mapsAreEqual(const BitVector &Mask, const AssignmentMap &A, 0
1060 const AssignmentMap &B) { ----
1061 return llvm::all_of(Mask.set_bits(), [&](unsigned VarID) { 0
1062 return A[VarID].isSameSourceAssignment(B[VarID]); 0
1063 }); 0
1064 } ----
1065 ----
1066 /// Represents the stack and debug assignments in a block. Used to describe ----
1067 /// the live-in and live-out values for blocks, as well as the "current" ----
1068 /// value as we process each instruction in a block. ----
1069 struct BlockInfo { ----
1070 /// The set of variables (VariableID) being tracked in this block. ----
1071 BitVector VariableIDsInBlock; ----
1072 /// Dominating assignment to memory for each variable, indexed by ----
1073 /// VariableID. ----
1074 AssignmentMap StackHomeValue; ----
1075 /// Dominating assignemnt to each variable, indexed by VariableID. ----
1076 AssignmentMap DebugValue; ----
1077 /// Location kind for each variable. LiveLoc indicates whether the ----
1078 /// dominating assignment in StackHomeValue (LocKind::Mem), DebugValue ----
1079 /// (LocKind::Val), or neither (LocKind::None) is valid, in that order of ----
1080 /// preference. This cannot be derived by inspecting DebugValue and ----
1081 /// StackHomeValue due to the fact that there's no distinction in ----
1082 /// Assignment (the class) between whether an assignment is unknown or a ----
1083 /// merge of multiple assignments (both are Status::NoneOrPhi). In other ----
1084 /// words, the memory location may well be valid while both DebugValue and ----
1085 /// StackHomeValue contain Assignments that have a Status of NoneOrPhi. ----
1086 /// Indexed by VariableID. ----
1087 LocMap LiveLoc; ----
1088 ----
1089 public: ----
1090 enum AssignmentKind { Stack, Debug }; ----
1091 const AssignmentMap &getAssignmentMap(AssignmentKind Kind) const { 0
1092 switch (Kind) { 0
1093 case Stack: 0
1094 return StackHomeValue; 0
1095 case Debug: 0
1096 return DebugValue; 0
1097 } ----
1098 llvm_unreachable("Unknown AssignmentKind"); 0
1099 } ----
1100 AssignmentMap &getAssignmentMap(AssignmentKind Kind) { 0
1101 return const_cast( ----
1102 const_cast(this)->getAssignmentMap(Kind)); 0
1103 } ----
1104 ----
1105 bool isVariableTracked(VariableID Var) const { 0
1106 return VariableIDsInBlock[static_cast(Var)]; 0
1107 } ----
1108 ----
1109 const Assignment &getAssignment(AssignmentKind Kind, VariableID Var) const { 0
1110 assert(isVariableTracked(Var) && "Var not tracked in block"); 0
1111 return getAssignmentMap(Kind)[static_cast(Var)]; 0
1112 } ----
1113 ----
1114 LocKind getLocKind(VariableID Var) const { 0
1115 assert(isVariableTracked(Var) && "Var not tracked in block"); 0
1116 return LiveLoc[static_cast(Var)]; 0
1117 } ----
1118 ----
1119 /// Set LocKind for \p Var only: does not set LocKind for VariableIDs of ----
1120 /// fragments contained win \p Var. ----
1121 void setLocKind(VariableID Var, LocKind K) { 0
1122 VariableIDsInBlock.set(static_cast(Var)); 0
1123 LiveLoc[static_cast(Var)] = K; 0
1124 } 0
1125 ----
1126 /// Set the assignment in the \p Kind assignment map for \p Var only: does ----
1127 /// not set the assignment for VariableIDs of fragments contained win \p ----
1128 /// Var. ----
1129 void setAssignment(AssignmentKind Kind, VariableID Var, 0
1130 const Assignment &AV) { ----
1131 VariableIDsInBlock.set(static_cast(Var)); 0
1132 getAssignmentMap(Kind)[static_cast(Var)] = AV; 0
1133 } 0
1134 ----
1135 /// Return true if there is an assignment matching \p AV in the \p Kind ----
1136 /// assignment map. Does consider assignments for VariableIDs of fragments ----
1137 /// contained win \p Var. ----
1138 bool hasAssignment(AssignmentKind Kind, VariableID Var, 0
1139 const Assignment &AV) const { ----
1140 if (!isVariableTracked(Var)) 0
1141 return false; 0
1142 return AV.isSameSourceAssignment(getAssignment(Kind, Var)); 0
1143 } ----
1144 ----
1145 /// Compare every element in each map to determine structural equality ----
1146 /// (slow). ----
1147 bool operator==(const BlockInfo &Other) const { 0
1148 return VariableIDsInBlock == Other.VariableIDsInBlock && 0
1149 LiveLoc == Other.LiveLoc && 0
1150 mapsAreEqual(VariableIDsInBlock, StackHomeValue, 0
1151 Other.StackHomeValue) && 0
1152 mapsAreEqual(VariableIDsInBlock, DebugValue, Other.DebugValue); 0
1153 } ----
1154 bool operator!=(const BlockInfo &Other) const { return !(*this == Other); } 0
1155 bool isValid() { 0
1156 return LiveLoc.size() == DebugValue.size() && 0
1157 LiveLoc.size() == StackHomeValue.size(); 0
1158 } ----
1159 ----
1160 /// Clear everything and initialise with -values for all variables. ----
1161 void init(int NumVars) { 0
1162 StackHomeValue.clear(); 0
1163 DebugValue.clear(); 0
1164 LiveLoc.clear(); 0
1165 VariableIDsInBlock = BitVector(NumVars); 0
1166 StackHomeValue.insert(StackHomeValue.begin(), NumVars, 0
1167 Assignment::makeNoneOrPhi()); 0
1168 DebugValue.insert(DebugValue.begin(), NumVars, 0
1169 Assignment::makeNoneOrPhi()); 0
1170 LiveLoc.insert(LiveLoc.begin(), NumVars, LocKind::None); 0
1171 } 0

1173 /// Helper for join. ----
1174 template ----
1175 static void joinElmt(int Index, SmallVector &Target, 0
1176 const SmallVector &A, ----
1177 const SmallVector &B, ----
1178 ElmtType (*Fn)(FnInputType, FnInputType)) { ----
1179 Target[Index] = Fn(A[Index], B[Index]); 0
1180 } 0
1181 ----
1182 /// See comment for AssignmentTrackingLowering::joinBlockInfo. ----
1183 static BlockInfo join(const BlockInfo &A, const BlockInfo &B, int NumVars) { 0
1184 // Join A and B. ----
1185 // ----
1186 // Intersect = join(a, b) for a in A, b in B where Var(a) == Var(b) ----
1187 // Difference = join(x, ) for x where Var(x) is in A xor B ----
1188 // Join = Intersect Difference ----
1189 // ----
1190 // This is achieved by performing a join on elements from A and B with ----
1191 // variables common to both A and B (join elements indexed by var ----
1192 // intersect), then adding -value elements for vars in A xor B. The ----
1193 // latter part is equivalent to performing join on elements with variables ----
1194 // in A xor B with the -value for the map element since join(x, ) = . ----
1195 // BlockInfo::init initializes all variable entries to the value so we ----
1196 // don't need to explicitly perform that step as Join.VariableIDsInBlock ----
1197 // is set to the union of the variables in A and B at the end of this ----
1198 // function. ----
1199 BlockInfo Join; 0
1200 Join.init(NumVars); 0
1201 ----
1202 BitVector Intersect = A.VariableIDsInBlock; 0
1203 Intersect &= B.VariableIDsInBlock; 0
1204 ----
1205 for (auto VarID : Intersect.set_bits()) { 0
1206 joinElmt(VarID, Join.LiveLoc, A.LiveLoc, B.LiveLoc, joinKind); 0
1207 joinElmt(VarID, Join.DebugValue, A.DebugValue, B.DebugValue, 0
1208 joinAssignment); ----
1209 joinElmt(VarID, Join.StackHomeValue, A.StackHomeValue, B.StackHomeValue, 0
1210 joinAssignment); ----
1211 } ----
1212 ----
1213 Join.VariableIDsInBlock = A.VariableIDsInBlock; 0
1214 Join.VariableIDsInBlock |= B.VariableIDsInBlock; 0
1215 assert(Join.isValid()); 0
1216 return Join; 0
1217 } 0
1218 }; ----
1219 ----
1220 Function &Fn; ----
1221 const DataLayout &Layout; ----
1222 const DenseSet *VarsWithStackSlot; ----
1223 FunctionVarLocsBuilder *FnVarLocs; ----
1224 DenseMap LiveIn; ----
1225 DenseMap LiveOut; ----

1228 DenseSet VarsTouchedThisFrame; ----
1229 ----
1230 /// The set of variables that sometimes are not located in their stack home. ----

1233 VariableID getVariableID(const DebugVariable &Var) { 0
1234 return static_cast(FnVarLocs->insertVariable(Var)); 0
1235 } ----
1236 ----
1237 /// Join the LiveOut values of preds that are contained in \p Visited into ----
1238 /// LiveIn[BB]. Return True if LiveIn[BB] has changed as a result. LiveIn[BB] ----
1239 /// values monotonically increase. See the @link joinMethods join methods ----
1240 /// @endlink documentation for more info. ----
1241 bool join(const BasicBlock &BB, const SmallPtrSet &Visited); ----
1242 ///@name joinMethods ----
1243 /// Functions that implement `join` (the least upper bound) for the ----
1244 /// join-semilattice types used in the dataflow. There is an explicit bottom ----
1245 /// value () for some types and and explicit top value () for all types. ----
1246 /// By definition: ----
1247 /// ----
1248 /// Join(A, B) >= A && Join(A, B) >= B ----
1249 /// Join(A, ) = A ----
1250 /// Join(A, ) = ----
1251 /// ----
1252 /// These invariants are important for monotonicity. ----
1253 /// ----
1254 /// For the map-type functions, all unmapped keys in an empty map are ----
1255 /// associated with a bottom value (). This represents their values being ----
1256 /// unknown. Unmapped keys in non-empty maps (joining two maps with a key ----
1257 /// only present in one) represents either a variable going out of scope or ----
1258 /// dropped debug info. It is assumed the key is associated with a top value ----
1259 /// () in this case (unknown location / assignment). ----
1260 ///@{ ----
1261 static LocKind joinKind(LocKind A, LocKind B); ----
1262 static Assignment joinAssignment(const Assignment &A, const Assignment &B); ----
1263 BlockInfo joinBlockInfo(const BlockInfo &A, const BlockInfo &B); ----
1264 ///@} ----
1265 ----
1266 /// Process the instructions in \p BB updating \p LiveSet along the way. \p ----
1267 /// LiveSet must be initialized with the current live-in locations before ----
1268 /// calling this. ----
1269 void process(BasicBlock &BB, BlockInfo *LiveSet); ----
1270 ///@name processMethods ----
1271 /// Methods to process instructions in order to update the LiveSet (current ----
1272 /// location information). ----
1273 ///@{ ----
1274 void processNonDbgInstruction(Instruction &I, BlockInfo *LiveSet); ----
1275 void processDbgInstruction(DbgInfoIntrinsic &I, BlockInfo *LiveSet); ----
1276 /// Update \p LiveSet after encountering an instruction with a DIAssignID ----
1277 /// attachment, \p I. ----
1278 void processTaggedInstruction(Instruction &I, BlockInfo *LiveSet); ----
1279 /// Update \p LiveSet after encountering an instruciton without a DIAssignID ----
1280 /// attachment, \p I. ----
1281 void processUntaggedInstruction(Instruction &I, BlockInfo *LiveSet); ----
1282 void processDbgAssign(DbgAssignIntrinsic &DAI, BlockInfo *LiveSet); ----
1283 void processDbgValue(DbgValueInst &DVI, BlockInfo *LiveSet); ----
1284 /// Add an assignment to memory for the variable /p Var. ----
1285 void addMemDef(BlockInfo *LiveSet, VariableID Var, const Assignment &AV); ----
1286 /// Add an assignment to the variable /p Var. ----
1287 void addDbgDef(BlockInfo *LiveSet, VariableID Var, const Assignment &AV); ----
1288 ///@} ----
1289 ----
1290 /// Set the LocKind for \p Var. ----
1291 void setLocKind(BlockInfo *LiveSet, VariableID Var, LocKind K); ----
1292 /// Get the live LocKind for a \p Var. Requires addMemDef or addDbgDef to ----
1293 /// have been called for \p Var first. ----
1294 LocKind getLocKind(BlockInfo *LiveSet, VariableID Var); ----
1295 /// Return true if \p Var has an assignment in \p M matching \p AV. ----
1296 bool hasVarWithAssignment(BlockInfo *LiveSet, BlockInfo::AssignmentKind Kind, ----
1297 VariableID Var, const Assignment &AV); ----
1298 /// Return the set of VariableIDs corresponding the fragments contained fully ----
1299 /// within the variable/fragment \p Var. ----
1300 ArrayRef getContainedFragments(VariableID Var) const; ----
1301 ----
1302 /// Mark \p Var as having been touched this frame. Note, this applies only ----
1303 /// to the exact fragment \p Var and not to any fragments contained within. ----
1304 void touchFragment(VariableID Var); ----
1305 ----
1306 /// Emit info for variables that are fully promoted. ----
1307 bool emitPromotedVarLocs(FunctionVarLocsBuilder *FnVarLocs); ----

1309 public: ----
1310 AssignmentTrackingLowering(Function &Fn, const DataLayout &Layout, 0

1312 : Fn(Fn), Layout(Layout), VarsWithStackSlot(VarsWithStackSlot) {} 0
1313 /// Run the analysis, adding variable location info to \p FnVarLocs. Returns ----
1314 /// true if any variable locations have been added to FnVarLocs. ----
1315 bool run(FunctionVarLocsBuilder *FnVarLocs); ----
1316 }; ----

1320 AssignmentTrackingLowering::getContainedFragments(VariableID Var) const { 0
1321 auto R = VarContains.find(Var); 0
1322 if (R == VarContains.end()) 0
1323 return std::nullopt; 0
1324 return R->second; 0

1331 void AssignmentTrackingLowering::setLocKind(BlockInfo *LiveSet, VariableID Var, 0
1332 LocKind K) { ----
1333 auto SetKind = [this](BlockInfo *LiveSet, VariableID Var, LocKind K) { 0
1334 LiveSet->setLocKind(Var, K); 0
1335 touchFragment(Var); 0
1336 }; 0
1337 SetKind(LiveSet, Var, K); 0
1338 ----
1339 // Update the LocKind for all fragments contained within Var. ----
1340 for (VariableID Frag : getContainedFragments(Var)) 0
1341 SetKind(LiveSet, Frag, K); 0
1342 } 0

1349 void AssignmentTrackingLowering::addMemDef(BlockInfo *LiveSet, VariableID Var, 0
1350 const Assignment &AV) { ----
1351 LiveSet->setAssignment(BlockInfo::Stack, Var, AV); 0
1352 ----
1353 // Use this assigment for all fragments contained within Var, but do not ----
1354 // provide a Source because we cannot convert Var's value to a value for the ----
1355 // fragment. ----
1356 Assignment FragAV = AV; 0
1357 FragAV.Source = nullptr; 0
1358 for (VariableID Frag : getContainedFragments(Var)) 0
1359 LiveSet->setAssignment(BlockInfo::Stack, Frag, FragAV); 0
1360 } 0

1362 void AssignmentTrackingLowering::addDbgDef(BlockInfo *LiveSet, VariableID Var, 0
1363 const Assignment &AV) { ----
1364 LiveSet->setAssignment(BlockInfo::Debug, Var, AV); 0
1365 ----
1366 // Use this assigment for all fragments contained within Var, but do not ----
1367 // provide a Source because we cannot convert Var's value to a value for the ----
1368 // fragment. ----
1369 Assignment FragAV = AV; 0
1370 FragAV.Source = nullptr; 0
1371 for (VariableID Frag : getContainedFragments(Var)) 0
1372 LiveSet->setAssignment(BlockInfo::Debug, Frag, FragAV); 0
1373 } 0

1376 return cast(I.getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_DIAssignID)); 0
1377 } ----

1382 ----
1383 /// Return true if \p Var has an assignment in \p M matching \p AV. ----
1384 bool AssignmentTrackingLowering::hasVarWithAssignment( 0
1385 BlockInfo *LiveSet, BlockInfo::AssignmentKind Kind, VariableID Var, ----
1386 const Assignment &AV) { ----
1387 if (!LiveSet->hasAssignment(Kind, Var, AV)) 0
1388 return false; 0
1389 ----
1390 // Check all the frags contained within Var as these will have all been ----
1391 // mapped to AV at the last store to Var. ----
1392 for (VariableID Frag : getContainedFragments(Var)) 0
1393 if (!LiveSet->hasAssignment(Kind, Frag, AV)) 0
1394 return false; 0
1395 return true; 0
1396 } ----
