1398 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
1399 const char *locStr(AssignmentTrackingLowering::LocKind Loc) { 0
1400 using LocKind = AssignmentTrackingLowering::LocKind; ----
1401 switch (Loc) { 0
1402 case LocKind::Val: 0
1403 return "Val"; 0
1404 case LocKind::Mem: 0
1405 return "Mem"; 0
1406 case LocKind::None: 0
1407 return "None"; 0
1408 }; ----
1409 llvm_unreachable("unknown LocKind"); 0
1410 } ----
1411 #endif ----
1412 ----
1413 void AssignmentTrackingLowering::emitDbgValue( 0
1414 AssignmentTrackingLowering::LocKind Kind, ----
1415 const DbgVariableIntrinsic *Source, Instruction *After) { ----
1416 ----
1417 DILocation *DL = Source->getDebugLoc(); 0
1418 auto Emit = [this, Source, After, DL](Metadata *Val, DIExpression *Expr) { 0
1419 assert(Expr); 0
1420 if (!Val) 0
1421 Val = ValueAsMetadata::get( 0
1422 PoisonValue::get(Type::getInt1Ty(Source->getContext()))); 0
1423 ----
1424 // Find a suitable insert point. ----
1425 Instruction *InsertBefore = After->getNextNode(); 0
1426 assert(InsertBefore && "Shouldn't be inserting after a terminator"); 0
1427 ----
1428 VariableID Var = getVariableID(DebugVariable(Source)); 0
1429 VarLocInfo VarLoc; 0
1430 VarLoc.VariableID = static_cast(Var); 0
1431 VarLoc.Expr = Expr; 0
1432 VarLoc.Values = RawLocationWrapper(Val); 0
1433 VarLoc.DL = DL; 0
1434 // Insert it into the map for later. ----
1435 InsertBeforeMap[InsertBefore].push_back(VarLoc); 0
1436 }; 0
1437 ----
1438 // NOTE: This block can mutate Kind. ----
1439 if (Kind == LocKind::Mem) { 0
1440 const auto *DAI = cast(Source); 0
1441 // Check the address hasn't been dropped (e.g. the debug uses may not have ----
1442 // been replaced before deleting a Value). ----
1443 if (DAI->isKillAddress()) { 0
1444 // The address isn't valid so treat this as a non-memory def. ----
1445 Kind = LocKind::Val; 0
1446 } else { ----
1447 Value *Val = DAI->getAddress(); 0
1448 DIExpression *Expr = DAI->getAddressExpression(); 0
1449 assert(!Expr->getFragmentInfo() && 0
1450 "fragment info should be stored in value-expression only"); ----
1451 // Copy the fragment info over from the value-expression to the new ----
1452 // DIExpression. ----
1453 if (auto OptFragInfo = Source->getExpression()->getFragmentInfo()) { 0
1454 auto FragInfo = *OptFragInfo; 0
1455 Expr = *DIExpression::createFragmentExpression( 0
1456 Expr, FragInfo.OffsetInBits, FragInfo.SizeInBits); 0
1457 } ----
1458 // The address-expression has an implicit deref, add it now. ----
1459 std::tie(Val, Expr) = 0
1460 walkToAllocaAndPrependOffsetDeref(Layout, Val, Expr); 0
1461 Emit(ValueAsMetadata::get(Val), Expr); 0
1462 return; 0
1463 } ----
1464 } ----
1465 ----
1466 if (Kind == LocKind::Val) { 0
1467 Emit(Source->getRawLocation(), Source->getExpression()); 0
1468 return; 0
1469 } ----
1470 ----
1471 if (Kind == LocKind::None) { 0
1472 Emit(nullptr, Source->getExpression()); 0
1473 return; 0
1474 } ----
1475 } ----
1476 ----
1477 void AssignmentTrackingLowering::processNonDbgInstruction( 0
1478 Instruction &I, AssignmentTrackingLowering::BlockInfo *LiveSet) { ----
1479 if (I.hasMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_DIAssignID)) 0
1480 processTaggedInstruction(I, LiveSet); 0
1481 else ----
1482 processUntaggedInstruction(I, LiveSet); 0
1483 } 0
1484 ----
1485 void AssignmentTrackingLowering::processUntaggedInstruction( 0
1486 Instruction &I, AssignmentTrackingLowering::BlockInfo *LiveSet) { ----
1487 // Interpret stack stores that are not tagged as an assignment in memory for ----
1488 // the variables associated with that address. These stores may not be tagged ----
1489 // because a) the store cannot be represented using dbg.assigns (non-const ----
1490 // length or offset) or b) the tag was accidentally dropped during ----
1491 // optimisations. For these stores we fall back to assuming that the stack ----
1492 // home is a valid location for the variables. The benefit is that this ----
1493 // prevents us missing an assignment and therefore incorrectly maintaining ----
1494 // earlier location definitions, and in many cases it should be a reasonable ----
1495 // assumption. However, this will occasionally lead to slight ----
1496 // inaccuracies. The value of a hoisted untagged store will be visible ----
1497 // "early", for example. ----
1498 assert(!I.hasMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_DIAssignID)); 0
1499 auto It = UntaggedStoreVars.find(&I); 0
1500 if (It == UntaggedStoreVars.end()) 0
1501 return; // No variables associated with the store destination. 0
1502 ----
1503 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "processUntaggedInstruction on UNTAGGED INST " << I 0
1504 << "\n"); ----
1505 // Iterate over the variables that this store affects, add a NoneOrPhi dbg ----
1506 // and mem def, set lockind to Mem, and emit a location def for each. ----
1507 for (auto [Var, Info] : It->second) { 0
1508 // This instruction is treated as both a debug and memory assignment, ----
1509 // meaning the memory location should be used. We don't have an assignment ----
1510 // ID though so use Assignment::makeNoneOrPhi() to create an imaginary one. ----
1511 addMemDef(LiveSet, Var, Assignment::makeNoneOrPhi()); 0
1512 addDbgDef(LiveSet, Var, Assignment::makeNoneOrPhi()); 0
1513 setLocKind(LiveSet, Var, LocKind::Mem); 0
1514 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " setting Stack LocKind to: " << locStr(LocKind::Mem) 0
1515 << "\n"); ----
1516 // Build the dbg location def to insert. ----
1517 // ----
1518 // DIExpression: Add fragment and offset. ----
1519 DebugVariable V = FnVarLocs->getVariable(Var); 0
1520 DIExpression *DIE = DIExpression::get(I.getContext(), std::nullopt); 0
1521 if (auto Frag = V.getFragment()) { 0
1522 auto R = DIExpression::createFragmentExpression(DIE, Frag->OffsetInBits, 0
1523 Frag->SizeInBits); 0
1524 assert(R && "unexpected createFragmentExpression failure"); 0
1525 DIE = *R; 0
1526 } ----
1527 SmallVector Ops; 0
1528 if (Info.OffsetInBits) 0
1529 Ops = {dwarf::DW_OP_plus_uconst, Info.OffsetInBits / 8}; 0
1530 Ops.push_back(dwarf::DW_OP_deref); 0
1531 DIE = DIExpression::prependOpcodes(DIE, Ops, /*StackValue=*/false, 0
1532 /*EntryValue=*/false); ----
1533 // Find a suitable insert point. ----
1534 Instruction *InsertBefore = I.getNextNode(); 0
1535 assert(InsertBefore && "Shouldn't be inserting after a terminator"); 0
1536 ----
1537 // Get DILocation for this unrecorded assignment. ----
1538 DILocation *InlinedAt = const_cast(V.getInlinedAt()); 0
1539 const DILocation *DILoc = DILocation::get( 0
1540 Fn.getContext(), 0, 0, V.getVariable()->getScope(), InlinedAt); 0
1541 ----
1542 VarLocInfo VarLoc; 0
1543 VarLoc.VariableID = static_cast(Var); 0
1544 VarLoc.Expr = DIE; 0
1545 VarLoc.Values = RawLocationWrapper( 0
1546 ValueAsMetadata::get(const_cast(Info.Base))); 0
1547 VarLoc.DL = DILoc; 0
1548 // 3. Insert it into the map for later. ----
1549 InsertBeforeMap[InsertBefore].push_back(VarLoc); 0
1550 } 0
1551 } ----
1552 ----
1553 void AssignmentTrackingLowering::processTaggedInstruction( 0
1554 Instruction &I, AssignmentTrackingLowering::BlockInfo *LiveSet) { ----
1555 auto Linked = at::getAssignmentMarkers(&I); 0
1556 // No dbg.assign intrinsics linked. ----
1557 // FIXME: All vars that have a stack slot this store modifies that don't have ----
1558 // a dbg.assign linked to it should probably treat this like an untagged ----
1559 // store. ----
1560 if (Linked.empty()) 0
1561 return; 0
1562 ----
1563 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "processTaggedInstruction on " << I << "\n"); 0
1564 for (DbgAssignIntrinsic *DAI : Linked) { 0
1565 VariableID Var = getVariableID(DebugVariable(DAI)); 0
1566 // Something has gone wrong if VarsWithStackSlot doesn't contain a variable ----
1567 // that is linked to a store. ----
1568 assert(VarsWithStackSlot->count(getAggregate(DAI)) && 0
1569 "expected DAI's variable to have stack slot"); ----
1570 ----
1571 Assignment AV = Assignment::makeFromMemDef(getIDFromInst(I)); 0
1572 addMemDef(LiveSet, Var, AV); 0
1573 ----
1574 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " linked to " << *DAI << "\n"); 0
1575 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " LiveLoc " << locStr(getLocKind(LiveSet, Var)) 0
1576 << " -> "); ----
1577 ----
1578 // The last assignment to the stack is now AV. Check if the last debug ----
1579 // assignment has a matching Assignment. ----
1580 if (hasVarWithAssignment(LiveSet, BlockInfo::Debug, Var, AV)) { 0
1581 // The StackHomeValue and DebugValue for this variable match so we can ----
1582 // emit a stack home location here. ----
1583 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Mem, Stack matches Debug program\n";); 0
1584 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Stack val: "; AV.dump(dbgs()); dbgs() << "\n"); 0
1585 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Debug val: "; 0
1586 LiveSet->DebugValue[static_cast(Var)].dump(dbgs()); ----
1587 dbgs() << "\n"); ----
1588 setLocKind(LiveSet, Var, LocKind::Mem); 0
1589 emitDbgValue(LocKind::Mem, DAI, &I); 0
1590 continue; 0
1591 } ----
1592 ----
1593 // The StackHomeValue and DebugValue for this variable do not match. I.e. ----
1594 // The value currently stored in the stack is not what we'd expect to ----
1595 // see, so we cannot use emit a stack home location here. Now we will ----
1596 // look at the live LocKind for the variable and determine an appropriate ----
1597 // dbg.value to emit. ----
1598 LocKind PrevLoc = getLocKind(LiveSet, Var); 0
1599 switch (PrevLoc) { 0
1600 case LocKind::Val: { 0
1601 // The value in memory in memory has changed but we're not currently ----
1602 // using the memory location. Do nothing. ----
1603 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Val, (unchanged)\n";); 0
1604 setLocKind(LiveSet, Var, LocKind::Val); 0
1605 } break; 0
1606 case LocKind::Mem: { 0
1607 // There's been an assignment to memory that we were using as a ----
1608 // location for this variable, and the Assignment doesn't match what ----
1609 // we'd expect to see in memory. ----
1610 Assignment DbgAV = LiveSet->getAssignment(BlockInfo::Debug, Var); 0
1611 if (DbgAV.Status == Assignment::NoneOrPhi) { 0
1612 // We need to terminate any previously open location now. ----
1613 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "None, No Debug value available\n";); 0
1614 setLocKind(LiveSet, Var, LocKind::None); 0
1615 emitDbgValue(LocKind::None, DAI, &I); 0
1616 } else { ----
1617 // The previous DebugValue Value can be used here. ----
1618 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Val, Debug value is Known\n";); 0
1619 setLocKind(LiveSet, Var, LocKind::Val); 0
1620 if (DbgAV.Source) { 0
1621 emitDbgValue(LocKind::Val, DbgAV.Source, &I); 0
1622 } else { ----
1623 // PrevAV.Source is nullptr so we must emit undef here. ----
1624 emitDbgValue(LocKind::None, DAI, &I); 0
1625 } ----
1626 } ----
1627 } break; 0
1628 case LocKind::None: { 0
1629 // There's been an assignment to memory and we currently are ----
1630 // not tracking a location for the variable. Do not emit anything. ----
1631 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "None, (unchanged)\n";); 0
1632 setLocKind(LiveSet, Var, LocKind::None); 0
1633 } break; 0
1634 } ----
1635 } ----
1636 } ----
1637 ----
1638 void AssignmentTrackingLowering::processDbgAssign(DbgAssignIntrinsic &DAI, 0
1639 BlockInfo *LiveSet) { ----
1640 // Only bother tracking variables that are at some point stack homed. Other ----
1641 // variables can be dealt with trivially later. ----
1642 if (!VarsWithStackSlot->count(getAggregate(&DAI))) 0
1643 return; 0
1644 ----
1645 VariableID Var = getVariableID(DebugVariable(&DAI)); 0
1646 Assignment AV = Assignment::make(getIDFromMarker(DAI), &DAI); 0
1647 addDbgDef(LiveSet, Var, AV); 0
1648 ----
1649 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "processDbgAssign on " << DAI << "\n";); 0
1650 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " LiveLoc " << locStr(getLocKind(LiveSet, Var)) 0
1651 << " -> "); ----
1652 ----
1653 // Check if the DebugValue and StackHomeValue both hold the same ----
1654 // Assignment. ----
1655 if (hasVarWithAssignment(LiveSet, BlockInfo::Stack, Var, AV)) { 0
1656 // They match. We can use the stack home because the debug intrinsics state ----
1657 // that an assignment happened here, and we know that specific assignment ----
1658 // was the last one to take place in memory for this variable. ----
1659 LocKind Kind; ----
1660 if (DAI.isKillAddress()) { 0
1661 LLVM_DEBUG( 0
1662 dbgs() ----
1663 << "Val, Stack matches Debug program but address is killed\n";); ----
1664 Kind = LocKind::Val; 0
1665 } else { ----
1666 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Mem, Stack matches Debug program\n";); 0
1667 Kind = LocKind::Mem; 0
1668 }; ----
1669 setLocKind(LiveSet, Var, Kind); 0
1670 emitDbgValue(Kind, &DAI, &DAI); 0
1671 } else { ----
1672 // The last assignment to the memory location isn't the one that we want to ----
1673 // show to the user so emit a dbg.value(Value). Value may be undef. ----
1674 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Val, Stack contents is unknown\n";); 0
1675 setLocKind(LiveSet, Var, LocKind::Val); 0
1676 emitDbgValue(LocKind::Val, &DAI, &DAI); 0
1677 } ----
1678 } ----
1679 ----
1680 void AssignmentTrackingLowering::processDbgValue(DbgValueInst &DVI, 0
1681 BlockInfo *LiveSet) { ----
1682 // Only other tracking variables that are at some point stack homed. ----
1683 // Other variables can be dealt with trivally later. ----
1684 if (!VarsWithStackSlot->count(getAggregate(&DVI))) 0
1685 return; 0
1686 ----
1687 VariableID Var = getVariableID(DebugVariable(&DVI)); 0
1688 // We have no ID to create an Assignment with so we mark this assignment as ----
1689 // NoneOrPhi. Note that the dbg.value still exists, we just cannot determine ----
1690 // the assignment responsible for setting this value. ----
1691 // This is fine; dbg.values are essentially interchangable with unlinked ----
1692 // dbg.assigns, and some passes such as mem2reg and instcombine add them to ----
1693 // PHIs for promoted variables. ----
1694 Assignment AV = Assignment::makeNoneOrPhi(); 0
1695 addDbgDef(LiveSet, Var, AV); 0
1696 ----
1697 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "processDbgValue on " << DVI << "\n";); 0
1698 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " LiveLoc " << locStr(getLocKind(LiveSet, Var)) 0
1699 << " -> Val, dbg.value override"); ----
1700 ----
1701 setLocKind(LiveSet, Var, LocKind::Val); 0
1702 emitDbgValue(LocKind::Val, &DVI, &DVI); 0
1703 } ----
1704 ----
1705 static bool hasZeroSizedFragment(DbgVariableIntrinsic &DVI) { 0
1706 if (auto F = DVI.getExpression()->getFragmentInfo()) 0
1707 return F->SizeInBits == 0; 0
1708 return false; 0
1709 } ----
1710 ----
1711 void AssignmentTrackingLowering::processDbgInstruction( 0
1712 DbgInfoIntrinsic &I, AssignmentTrackingLowering::BlockInfo *LiveSet) { ----
1713 auto *DVI = dyn_cast(&I); 0
1714 if (!DVI) 0
1715 return; 0
1716 ----
1717 // Ignore assignments to zero bits of the variable. ----
1718 if (hasZeroSizedFragment(*DVI)) 0
1719 return; 0
1720 ----
1721 if (auto *DAI = dyn_cast(&I)) 0
1722 processDbgAssign(*DAI, LiveSet); 0
1723 else if (auto *DVI = dyn_cast(&I)) 0
1724 processDbgValue(*DVI, LiveSet); 0
1725 } ----
1726 ----
1727 void AssignmentTrackingLowering::resetInsertionPoint(Instruction &After) { 0
1728 assert(!After.isTerminator() && "Can't insert after a terminator"); 0
1729 auto R = InsertBeforeMap.find(After.getNextNode()); 0
1730 if (R == InsertBeforeMap.end()) 0
1731 return; 0
1732 R->second.clear(); 0
1733 } ----
1734 ----
1735 void AssignmentTrackingLowering::process(BasicBlock &BB, BlockInfo *LiveSet) { 0
1736 for (auto II = BB.begin(), EI = BB.end(); II != EI;) { 0
1737 assert(VarsTouchedThisFrame.empty()); 0
1738 // Process the instructions in "frames". A "frame" includes a single ----
1739 // non-debug instruction followed any debug instructions before the ----
1740 // next non-debug instruction. ----
1741 if (!isa(&*II)) { 0
1742 if (II->isTerminator()) 0
1743 break; 0
1744 resetInsertionPoint(*II); 0
1745 processNonDbgInstruction(*II, LiveSet); 0
1746 assert(LiveSet->isValid()); 0
1747 ++II; 0
1748 } ----
1749 while (II != EI) { 0
1750 auto *Dbg = dyn_cast(&*II); 0
1751 if (!Dbg) 0
1752 break; 0
1753 resetInsertionPoint(*II); 0
1754 processDbgInstruction(*Dbg, LiveSet); 0
1755 assert(LiveSet->isValid()); 0
1756 ++II; 0
1757 } ----
1758 ----
1759 // We've processed everything in the "frame". Now determine which variables ----
1760 // cannot be represented by a dbg.declare. ----
1761 for (auto Var : VarsTouchedThisFrame) { 0
1762 LocKind Loc = getLocKind(LiveSet, Var); 0
1763 // If a variable's LocKind is anything other than LocKind::Mem then we ----
1764 // must note that it cannot be represented with a dbg.declare. ----
1765 // Note that this check is enough without having to check the result of ----
1766 // joins() because for join to produce anything other than Mem after ----
1767 // we've already seen a Mem we'd be joining None or Val with Mem. In that ----
1768 // case, we've already hit this codepath when we set the LocKind to Val ----
1769 // or None in that block. ----
1770 if (Loc != LocKind::Mem) { 0
1771 DebugVariable DbgVar = FnVarLocs->getVariable(Var); 0
1772 DebugAggregate Aggr{DbgVar.getVariable(), DbgVar.getInlinedAt()}; 0
1773 NotAlwaysStackHomed.insert(Aggr); 0
1774 } ----
1775 } ----
1776 VarsTouchedThisFrame.clear(); 0
1777 } ----
1778 } 0
1779 ----
1780 AssignmentTrackingLowering::LocKind ----
1781 AssignmentTrackingLowering::joinKind(LocKind A, LocKind B) { 0
1782 // Partial order: ----
1783 // None > Mem, Val ----
1784 return A == B ? A : LocKind::None; 0
1785 } ----
1786 ----
1787 AssignmentTrackingLowering::Assignment ----
1788 AssignmentTrackingLowering::joinAssignment(const Assignment &A, 0
1789 const Assignment &B) { ----
1790 // Partial order: ----
1791 // NoneOrPhi(null, null) > Known(v, ?s) ----
1792 ----
1793 // If either are NoneOrPhi the join is NoneOrPhi. ----
1794 // If either value is different then the result is ----
1795 // NoneOrPhi (joining two values is a Phi). ----
1796 if (!A.isSameSourceAssignment(B)) 0
1797 return Assignment::makeNoneOrPhi(); 0
1798 if (A.Status == Assignment::NoneOrPhi) 0
1799 return Assignment::makeNoneOrPhi(); 0
1800 ----
1801 // Source is used to lookup the value + expression in the debug program if ----
1802 // the stack slot gets assigned a value earlier than expected. Because ----
1803 // we're only tracking the one dbg.assign, we can't capture debug PHIs. ----
1804 // It's unlikely that we're losing out on much coverage by avoiding that ----
1805 // extra work. ----
1806 // The Source may differ in this situation: ----
1807 // Pred.1: ----
1808 // dbg.assign i32 0, ..., !1, ... ----
1809 // Pred.2: ----
1810 // dbg.assign i32 1, ..., !1, ... ----
1811 // Here the same assignment (!1) was performed in both preds in the source, ----
1812 // but we can't use either one unless they are identical (e.g. .we don't ----
1813 // want to arbitrarily pick between constant values). ----
1814 auto JoinSource = [&]() -> DbgAssignIntrinsic * { 0
1815 if (A.Source == B.Source) 0
1816 return A.Source; 0
1817 if (A.Source == nullptr || B.Source == nullptr) 0
1818 return nullptr; 0
1819 if (A.Source->isIdenticalTo(B.Source)) 0
1820 return A.Source; 0
1821 return nullptr; 0
1822 }; 0
1823 DbgAssignIntrinsic *Source = JoinSource(); 0
1824 assert(A.Status == B.Status && A.Status == Assignment::Known); 0
1825 assert(A.ID == B.ID); 0
1826 return Assignment::make(A.ID, Source); 0
1827 } ----
1828 ----
1829 AssignmentTrackingLowering::BlockInfo ----
1830 AssignmentTrackingLowering::joinBlockInfo(const BlockInfo &A, 0
1831 const BlockInfo &B) { ----
1832 return BlockInfo::join(A, B, TrackedVariablesVectorSize); 0
1833 } ----
1834 ----
1835 bool AssignmentTrackingLowering::join( 0
1836 const BasicBlock &BB, const SmallPtrSet &Visited) { ----
1837 ----
1838 SmallVector VisitedPreds; 0
1839 // Ignore backedges if we have not visited the predecessor yet. As the ----
1840 // predecessor hasn't yet had locations propagated into it, most locations ----
1841 // will not yet be valid, so treat them as all being uninitialized and ----
1842 // potentially valid. If a location guessed to be correct here is ----
1843 // invalidated later, we will remove it when we revisit this block. This ----
1844 // is essentially the same as initialising all LocKinds and Assignments to ----
1845 // an implicit value which is the identity value for the join operation. ----
1846 for (auto I = pred_begin(&BB), E = pred_end(&BB); I != E; I++) { 0
1847 const BasicBlock *Pred = *I; 0
1848 if (Visited.count(Pred)) 0
1849 VisitedPreds.push_back(Pred); 0
1850 } ----
1851 ----
1852 // No preds visited yet. ----
1853 if (VisitedPreds.empty()) { 0
1854 auto It = LiveIn.try_emplace(&BB, BlockInfo()); 0
1855 bool DidInsert = It.second; 0
1856 if (DidInsert) 0
1857 It.first->second.init(TrackedVariablesVectorSize); 0
1858 return /*Changed*/ DidInsert; 0
1859 } ----
1860 ----
1861 // Exactly one visited pred. Copy the LiveOut from that pred into BB LiveIn. ----
1862 if (VisitedPreds.size() == 1) { 0
1863 const BlockInfo &PredLiveOut = LiveOut.find(VisitedPreds[0])->second; 0
1864 auto CurrentLiveInEntry = LiveIn.find(&BB); 0
1865 ----
1866 // Check if there isn't an entry, or there is but the LiveIn set has ----
1867 // changed (expensive check). ----
1868 if (CurrentLiveInEntry == LiveIn.end()) 0
1869 LiveIn.insert(std::make_pair(&BB, PredLiveOut)); 0
1870 else if (PredLiveOut != CurrentLiveInEntry->second) 0
1871 CurrentLiveInEntry->second = PredLiveOut; 0
1872 else ----
1873 return /*Changed*/ false; 0
1874 return /*Changed*/ true; 0
1875 } ----
1876 ----
1877 // More than one pred. Join LiveOuts of blocks 1 and 2. ----
1878 assert(VisitedPreds.size() > 1); 0
1879 const BlockInfo &PredLiveOut0 = LiveOut.find(VisitedPreds[0])->second; 0
1880 const BlockInfo &PredLiveOut1 = LiveOut.find(VisitedPreds[1])->second; 0
1881 BlockInfo BBLiveIn = joinBlockInfo(PredLiveOut0, PredLiveOut1); 0
1882 ----
1883 // Join the LiveOuts of subsequent blocks. ----
1884 ArrayRef Tail = ArrayRef(VisitedPreds).drop_front(2); 0
1885 for (const BasicBlock *Pred : Tail) { 0
1886 const auto &PredLiveOut = LiveOut.find(Pred); 0
1887 assert(PredLiveOut != LiveOut.end() && 0
1888 "block should have been processed already"); ----
1889 BBLiveIn = joinBlockInfo(std::move(BBLiveIn), PredLiveOut->second); 0
1890 } ----
1891 ----
1892 // Save the joined result for BB. ----
1893 auto CurrentLiveInEntry = LiveIn.find(&BB); 0
1894 // Check if there isn't an entry, or there is but the LiveIn set has changed ----
1895 // (expensive check). ----
1896 if (CurrentLiveInEntry == LiveIn.end()) 0
1897 LiveIn.try_emplace(&BB, std::move(BBLiveIn)); 0
1898 else if (BBLiveIn != CurrentLiveInEntry->second) 0
1899 CurrentLiveInEntry->second = std::move(BBLiveIn); 0
1900 else ----
1901 return /*Changed*/ false; 0
1902 return /*Changed*/ true; 0
1903 } 0
1904 ----
1905 /// Return true if A fully contains B. ----
1906 static bool fullyContains(DIExpression::FragmentInfo A, 0
1907 DIExpression::FragmentInfo B) { ----
1908 auto ALeft = A.OffsetInBits; 0
1909 auto BLeft = B.OffsetInBits; 0
1910 if (BLeft < ALeft) 0
1911 return false; 0
1912 ----
1913 auto ARight = ALeft + A.SizeInBits; 0
1914 auto BRight = BLeft + B.SizeInBits; 0
1915 if (BRight > ARight) 0
1916 return false; 0
1917 return true; 0
1918 } ----
1919 ----
1920 static std::optional ----
1921 getUntaggedStoreAssignmentInfo(const Instruction &I, const DataLayout &Layout) { 0
1922 // Don't bother checking if this is an AllocaInst. We know this ----
1923 // instruction has no tag which means there are no variables associated ----
1924 // with it. ----
1925 if (const auto *SI = dyn_cast(&I)) 0
1926 return at::getAssignmentInfo(Layout, SI); 0
1927 if (const auto *MI = dyn_cast(&I)) 0
1928 return at::getAssignmentInfo(Layout, MI); 0
1929 // Alloca or non-store-like inst. ----
1930 return std::nullopt; 0
1931 } ----
1932 ----
1933 /// Build a map of {Variable x: Variables y} where all variable fragments ----
1934 /// contained within the variable fragment x are in set y. This means that ----
1935 /// y does not contain all overlaps because partial overlaps are excluded. ----
1936 /// ----
1937 /// While we're iterating over the function, add single location defs for ----
1938 /// dbg.declares to \p FnVarLocs. ----
1939 /// ----
1940 /// Variables that are interesting to this pass in are added to ----
1941 /// FnVarLocs->Variables first. TrackedVariablesVectorSize is set to the ID of ----
1942 /// the last interesting variable plus 1, meaning variables with ID 1 ----
1943 /// (inclusive) to TrackedVariablesVectorSize (exclusive) are interesting. The ----
1944 /// subsequent variables are either stack homed or fully promoted. ----
1945 /// ----
1946 /// Finally, populate UntaggedStoreVars with a mapping of untagged stores to ----
1947 /// the stored-to variable fragments. ----
1948 /// ----
1949 /// These tasks are bundled together to reduce the number of times we need ----
1950 /// to iterate over the function as they can be achieved together in one pass. ----
1951 static AssignmentTrackingLowering::OverlapMap buildOverlapMapAndRecordDeclares( 0
1952 Function &Fn, FunctionVarLocsBuilder *FnVarLocs, ----
1953 const DenseSet &VarsWithStackSlot, ----
1954 AssignmentTrackingLowering::UntaggedStoreAssignmentMap &UntaggedStoreVars, ----
1955 unsigned &TrackedVariablesVectorSize) { ----
1956 DenseSet Seen; 0
1957 // Map of Variable: [Fragments]. ----
1958 DenseMap> FragmentMap; 0
1959 // Iterate over all instructions: ----
1960 // - dbg.declare -> add single location variable record ----
1961 // - dbg.* -> Add fragments to FragmentMap ----
1962 // - untagged store -> Add fragments to FragmentMap and update ----
1963 // UntaggedStoreVars. ----
1964 // We need to add fragments for untagged stores too so that we can correctly ----
1965 // clobber overlapped fragment locations later. ----
1966 SmallVector Declares; 0
1967 for (auto &BB : Fn) { 0
1968 for (auto &I : BB) { 0
1969 if (auto *DDI = dyn_cast(&I)) { 0
1970 Declares.push_back(DDI); 0
1971 } else if (auto *DII = dyn_cast(&I)) { 0
1972 DebugVariable DV = DebugVariable(DII); 0
1973 DebugAggregate DA = {DV.getVariable(), DV.getInlinedAt()}; 0
1974 if (!VarsWithStackSlot.contains(DA)) 0
1975 continue; 0
1976 if (Seen.insert(DV).second) 0
1977 FragmentMap[DA].push_back(DV); 0
1978 } else if (auto Info = getUntaggedStoreAssignmentInfo( 0
1979 I, Fn.getParent()->getDataLayout())) { 0
1980 // Find markers linked to this alloca. ----
1981 for (DbgAssignIntrinsic *DAI : at::getAssignmentMarkers(Info->Base)) { 0
1982 // Discard the fragment if it covers the entire variable. ----
1983 std::optional FragInfo = ----
1984 [&Info, DAI]() -> std::optional { 0
1985 DIExpression::FragmentInfo F; ----
1986 F.OffsetInBits = Info->OffsetInBits; 0
1987 F.SizeInBits = Info->SizeInBits; 0
1988 if (auto ExistingFrag = DAI->getExpression()->getFragmentInfo()) 0
1989 F.OffsetInBits += ExistingFrag->OffsetInBits; 0
1990 if (auto Sz = DAI->getVariable()->getSizeInBits()) { 0
1991 if (F.OffsetInBits == 0 && F.SizeInBits == *Sz) 0
1992 return std::nullopt; 0
1993 } ----
1994 return F; 0
1995 }(); 0
1996 ----
1997 DebugVariable DV = DebugVariable(DAI->getVariable(), FragInfo, 0
1998 DAI->getDebugLoc().getInlinedAt()); 0
1999 DebugAggregate DA = {DV.getVariable(), DV.getInlinedAt()}; 0
2000 if (!VarsWithStackSlot.contains(DA)) 0
2001 continue; 0
2002 ----
2003 // Cache this info for later. ----
2004 UntaggedStoreVars[&I].push_back( 0
2005 {FnVarLocs->insertVariable(DV), *Info}); 0
2006 ----
2007 if (Seen.insert(DV).second) 0
2008 FragmentMap[DA].push_back(DV); 0
2009 } ----
2010 } ----
2011 } ----
2012 } ----
2013 ----
2014 // Sort the fragment map for each DebugAggregate in ascending ----
2015 // order of fragment size - there should be no duplicates. ----
2016 for (auto &Pair : FragmentMap) { 0
2017 SmallVector &Frags = Pair.second; 0
2018 std::sort(Frags.begin(), Frags.end(), 0
2019 [](const DebugVariable &Next, const DebugVariable &Elmt) { 0
2020 return Elmt.getFragmentOrDefault().SizeInBits > 0
2021 Next.getFragmentOrDefault().SizeInBits; 0
2022 }); ----
2023 // Check for duplicates. ----
2024 assert(std::adjacent_find(Frags.begin(), Frags.end()) == Frags.end()); 0
2025 } ----
2026 ----
2027 // Build the map. ----
2028 AssignmentTrackingLowering::OverlapMap Map; 0
2029 for (auto &Pair : FragmentMap) { 0
2030 auto &Frags = Pair.second; 0
2031 for (auto It = Frags.begin(), IEnd = Frags.end(); It != IEnd; ++It) { 0
2032 DIExpression::FragmentInfo Frag = It->getFragmentOrDefault(); 0
2033 // Find the frags that this is contained within. ----
2034 // ----
2035 // Because Frags is sorted by size and none have the same offset and ----
2036 // size, we know that this frag can only be contained by subsequent ----
2037 // elements. ----
2038 SmallVector::iterator OtherIt = It; 0
2039 ++OtherIt; 0
2040 VariableID ThisVar = FnVarLocs->insertVariable(*It); 0
2041 for (; OtherIt != IEnd; ++OtherIt) { 0
2042 DIExpression::FragmentInfo OtherFrag = OtherIt->getFragmentOrDefault(); 0
2043 VariableID OtherVar = FnVarLocs->insertVariable(*OtherIt); 0
2044 if (fullyContains(OtherFrag, Frag)) 0
2045 Map[OtherVar].push_back(ThisVar); 0
2046 } ----
2047 } ----
2048 } ----
2049 ----
2050 // VariableIDs are 1-based so the variable-tracking bitvector needs ----
2051 // NumVariables plus 1 bits. ----
2052 TrackedVariablesVectorSize = FnVarLocs->getNumVariables() + 1; 0
2053 ----
2054 // Finally, insert the declares afterwards, so the first IDs are all ----
2055 // partially stack homed vars. ----
2056 for (auto *DDI : Declares) 0
2057 FnVarLocs->addSingleLocVar(DebugVariable(DDI), DDI->getExpression(), 0
2058 DDI->getDebugLoc(), DDI->getWrappedLocation()); ----
2059 return Map; 0
2060 } 0
2061 ----
2062 bool AssignmentTrackingLowering::run(FunctionVarLocsBuilder *FnVarLocsBuilder) { 0
2063 if (Fn.size() > MaxNumBlocks) { 0
2064 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "[AT] Dropping var locs in: " << Fn.getName() 0
2065 << ": too many blocks (" << Fn.size() << ")\n"); ----
2066 at::deleteAll(&Fn); 0
2067 return false; 0
2068 } ----
2069 ----
2070 FnVarLocs = FnVarLocsBuilder; 0
2071 ----
2072 // The general structure here is inspired by VarLocBasedImpl.cpp ----
2073 // (LiveDebugValues). ----
2074 ----
2075 // Build the variable fragment overlap map. ----
2076 // Note that this pass doesn't handle partial overlaps correctly (FWIW ----
2077 // neither does LiveDebugVariables) because that is difficult to do and ----
2078 // appears to be rare occurance. ----
2079 VarContains = buildOverlapMapAndRecordDeclares( 0
2080 Fn, FnVarLocs, *VarsWithStackSlot, UntaggedStoreVars, 0
2081 TrackedVariablesVectorSize); 0
2082 ----
2083 // Prepare for traversal. ----
2084 ReversePostOrderTraversal RPOT(&Fn); 0
2085 std::priority_queue, ----
2086 std::greater> ----
2087 Worklist; 0
2088 std::priority_queue, ----
2089 std::greater> ----
2090 Pending; 0
2091 DenseMap OrderToBB; 0
2092 DenseMap BBToOrder; 0
2093 { // Init OrderToBB and BBToOrder. ----
2094 unsigned int RPONumber = 0; 0
2095 for (auto RI = RPOT.begin(), RE = RPOT.end(); RI != RE; ++RI) { 0
2096 OrderToBB[RPONumber] = *RI; 0
2097 BBToOrder[*RI] = RPONumber; 0
2098 Worklist.push(RPONumber); 0
2099 ++RPONumber; 0
2100 } ----
2101 LiveIn.init(RPONumber); 0
2102 LiveOut.init(RPONumber); 0
2103 } ----
2104 ----
2105 // Perform the traversal. ----
2106 // ----
2107 // This is a standard "union of predecessor outs" dataflow problem. To solve ----
2108 // it, we perform join() and process() using the two worklist method until ----
2109 // the LiveIn data for each block becomes unchanging. The "proof" that this ----
2110 // terminates can be put together by looking at the comments around LocKind, ----
2111 // Assignment, and the various join methods, which show that all the elements ----
2112 // involved are made up of join-semilattices; LiveIn(n) can only ----
2113 // monotonically increase in value throughout the dataflow. ----
2114 // ----
2115 SmallPtrSet Visited; 0
2116 while (!Worklist.empty()) { 0
2117 // We track what is on the pending worklist to avoid inserting the same ----
2118 // thing twice. ----
2119 SmallPtrSet OnPending; 0
2120 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Processing Worklist\n"); 0
2121 while (!Worklist.empty()) { 0
2122 BasicBlock *BB = OrderToBB[Worklist.top()]; 0
2123 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\nPop BB " << BB->getName() << "\n"); 0
2124 Worklist.pop(); 0
2125 bool InChanged = join(*BB, Visited); 0
2126 // Always consider LiveIn changed on the first visit. ----
2127 InChanged |= Visited.insert(BB).second; 0
2128 if (InChanged) { 0
2129 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << BB->getName() << " has new InLocs, process it\n"); 0
2130 // Mutate a copy of LiveIn while processing BB. After calling process ----
2131 // LiveSet is the LiveOut set for BB. ----
2132 BlockInfo LiveSet = LiveIn[BB]; 0
2133 ----
2134 // Process the instructions in the block. ----
2135 process(*BB, &LiveSet); 0
2136 ----
2137 // Relatively expensive check: has anything changed in LiveOut for BB? ----
2138 if (LiveOut[BB] != LiveSet) { 0
2139 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << BB->getName() 0
2140 << " has new OutLocs, add succs to worklist: [ "); ----
2141 LiveOut[BB] = std::move(LiveSet); 0
2142 for (auto I = succ_begin(BB), E = succ_end(BB); I != E; I++) { 0
2143 if (OnPending.insert(*I).second) { 0
2144 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << I->getName() << " "); 0
2145 Pending.push(BBToOrder[*I]); 0
2146 } ----
2147 } ----
2148 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "]\n"); 0
2149 } ----
2150 } 0
2151 } ----
2152 Worklist.swap(Pending); 0
2153 // At this point, pending must be empty, since it was just the empty ----
2154 // worklist ----
2155 assert(Pending.empty() && "Pending should be empty"); 0
2156 } 0
2157 ----
2158 // That's the hard part over. Now we just have some admin to do. ----
2159 ----
2160 // Record whether we inserted any intrinsics. ----
2161 bool InsertedAnyIntrinsics = false; 0
2162 ----
2163 // Identify and add defs for single location variables. ----
2164 // ----
2165 // Go through all of the defs that we plan to add. If the aggregate variable ----
2166 // it's a part of is not in the NotAlwaysStackHomed set we can emit a single ----
2167 // location def and omit the rest. Add an entry to AlwaysStackHomed so that ----
2168 // we can identify those uneeded defs later. ----
2169 DenseSet AlwaysStackHomed; 0
2170 for (const auto &Pair : InsertBeforeMap) { 0
2171 const auto &Vec = Pair.second; 0
2172 for (VarLocInfo VarLoc : Vec) { 0
2173 DebugVariable Var = FnVarLocs->getVariable(VarLoc.VariableID); 0
2174 DebugAggregate Aggr{Var.getVariable(), Var.getInlinedAt()}; 0
2175 ----
2176 // Skip this Var if it's not always stack homed. ----
2177 if (NotAlwaysStackHomed.contains(Aggr)) 0
2178 continue; 0
2179 ----
2180 // Skip complex cases such as when different fragments of a variable have ----
2181 // been split into different allocas. Skipping in this case means falling ----
2182 // back to using a list of defs (which could reduce coverage, but is no ----
2183 // less correct). ----
2184 bool Simple = ----
2185 VarLoc.Expr->getNumElements() == 1 && VarLoc.Expr->startsWithDeref(); 0
2186 if (!Simple) { 0
2187 NotAlwaysStackHomed.insert(Aggr); 0
2188 continue; 0
2189 } ----
2190 ----
2191 // All source assignments to this variable remain and all stores to any ----
2192 // part of the variable store to the same address (with varying ----
2193 // offsets). We can just emit a single location for the whole variable. ----
2194 // ----
2195 // Unless we've already done so, create the single location def now. ----
2196 if (AlwaysStackHomed.insert(Aggr).second) { 0
2197 assert(!VarLoc.Values.hasArgList()); 0
2198 // TODO: When more complex cases are handled VarLoc.Expr should be ----
2199 // built appropriately rather than always using an empty DIExpression. ----
2200 // The assert below is a reminder. ----
2201 assert(Simple); 0
2202 VarLoc.Expr = DIExpression::get(Fn.getContext(), std::nullopt); 0
2203 DebugVariable Var = FnVarLocs->getVariable(VarLoc.VariableID); 0
2204 FnVarLocs->addSingleLocVar(Var, VarLoc.Expr, VarLoc.DL, VarLoc.Values); 0
2205 InsertedAnyIntrinsics = true; 0
2206 } ----
2207 } 0
2208 } ----
2209 ----
2210 // Insert the other DEFs. ----
2211 for (const auto &[InsertBefore, Vec] : InsertBeforeMap) { 0
2212 SmallVector NewDefs; 0
2213 for (const VarLocInfo &VarLoc : Vec) { 0
2214 DebugVariable Var = FnVarLocs->getVariable(VarLoc.VariableID); 0
2215 DebugAggregate Aggr{Var.getVariable(), Var.getInlinedAt()}; 0
2216 // If this variable is always stack homed then we have already inserted a ----
2217 // dbg.declare and deleted this dbg.value. ----
2218 if (AlwaysStackHomed.contains(Aggr)) 0
2219 continue; 0
2220 NewDefs.push_back(VarLoc); 0
2221 InsertedAnyIntrinsics = true; 0
2222 } ----
2223 ----
2224 FnVarLocs->setWedge(InsertBefore, std::move(NewDefs)); 0
2225 } 0
2226 ----
2227 InsertedAnyIntrinsics |= emitPromotedVarLocs(FnVarLocs); 0
2228 ----
2229 return InsertedAnyIntrinsics; 0
2230 } 0
2231 ----
2232 bool AssignmentTrackingLowering::emitPromotedVarLocs( 0
2233 FunctionVarLocsBuilder *FnVarLocs) { ----
2234 bool InsertedAnyIntrinsics = false; 0
2235 // Go through every block, translating debug intrinsics for fully promoted ----
2236 // variables into FnVarLocs location defs. No analysis required for these. ----
2237 for (auto &BB : Fn) { 0
2238 for (auto &I : BB) { 0
2239 // Skip instructions other than dbg.values and dbg.assigns. ----
2240 auto *DVI = dyn_cast(&I); 0
2241 if (!DVI) 0
2242 continue; 0
2243 // Skip variables that haven't been promoted - we've dealt with those ----
2244 // already. ----
2245 if (VarsWithStackSlot->contains(getAggregate(DVI))) 0
2246 continue; 0
2247 Instruction *InsertBefore = I.getNextNode(); 0
2248 assert(InsertBefore && "Unexpected: debug intrinsics after a terminator"); 0
2249 FnVarLocs->addVarLoc(InsertBefore, DebugVariable(DVI), 0
2250 DVI->getExpression(), DVI->getDebugLoc(), ----
2251 DVI->getWrappedLocation()); ----
2252 InsertedAnyIntrinsics = true; 0
2253 } ----
2254 } ----
2255 return InsertedAnyIntrinsics; 0
2256 } ----
2257 ----
2258 /// Remove redundant definitions within sequences of consecutive location defs. ----
2259 /// This is done using a backward scan to keep the last def describing a ----
2260 /// specific variable/fragment. ----
2261 /// ----
2262 /// This implements removeRedundantDbgInstrsUsingBackwardScan from ----
2263 /// lib/Transforms/Utils/BasicBlockUtils.cpp for locations described with ----
2264 /// FunctionVarLocsBuilder instead of with intrinsics. ----
2265 static bool ----
2266 removeRedundantDbgLocsUsingBackwardScan(const BasicBlock *BB, 0
2267 FunctionVarLocsBuilder &FnVarLocs) { ----
2268 bool Changed = false; 0
2269 SmallDenseMap VariableDefinedBits; 0

2273 for (const Instruction &I : reverse(*BB)) { 0
2274 if (!isa(I)) { 0

2281 if (!Locs) 0
2282 continue; 0

2284 NumWedgesScanned++; 0

2286 // The new pruned set of defs, reversed because we're scanning backwards. ----
2287 SmallVector NewDefsReversed; 0
2288 ----
2289 // Iterate over the existing defs in reverse. ----
2290 for (auto RIt = Locs->rbegin(), REnd = Locs->rend(); RIt != REnd; ++RIt) { 0
2291 NumDefsScanned++; 0

2298 NewDefsReversed.push_back(*RIt); 0

2312 RIt->Expr->getFragmentInfo().value_or( 0
2313 DIExpression::FragmentInfo(SizeInBits, 0)); 0
2314 bool InvalidFragment = Fragment.endInBits() > SizeInBits; 0
2315 ----
2316 // If this defines any previously undefined bits, keep it. ----
2317 if (FirstDefinition || InvalidFragment || 0
2318 DefinedBits.find_first_unset_in(Fragment.startInBits(), 0
2319 Fragment.endInBits()) != -1) { 0
2320 if (!InvalidFragment) 0
2321 DefinedBits.set(Fragment.startInBits(), Fragment.endInBits()); 0
2322 NewDefsReversed.push_back(*RIt); 0
2323 continue; 0
2324 } ----
2325 ----
2326 // Redundant def found: throw it away. Since the wedge of defs is being ----
2327 // rebuilt, doing nothing is the same as deleting an entry. ----
2328 ChangedThisWedge = true; 0
2329 NumDefsRemoved++; 0
2330 } ----
2331 ----
2332 // Un-reverse the defs and replace the wedge with the pruned version. ----
2333 if (ChangedThisWedge) { 0
2334 std::reverse(NewDefsReversed.begin(), NewDefsReversed.end()); 0
2335 FnVarLocs.setWedge(&I, std::move(NewDefsReversed)); 0
2336 NumWedgesChanged++; 0
2337 Changed = true; 0
2338 } ----
2339 } 0
2340 ----
2341 return Changed; 0
2342 } 0

2344 /// Remove redundant location defs using a forward scan. This can remove a ----
2345 /// location definition that is redundant due to indicating that a variable has ----
2346 /// the same value as is already being indicated by an earlier def. ----
2347 /// ----
2348 /// This implements removeRedundantDbgInstrsUsingForwardScan from ----

2404 static bool ----
2405 removeUndefDbgLocsFromEntryBlock(const BasicBlock *BB, 0
2406 FunctionVarLocsBuilder &FnVarLocs) { ----
2407 assert(BB->isEntryBlock()); 0
2408 // Do extra work to ensure that we remove semantically unimportant undefs. ----
2409 // ----
2410 // This is to work around the fact that SelectionDAG will hoist dbg.values ----
2411 // using argument values to the top of the entry block. That can move arg ----
2412 // dbg.values before undef and constant dbg.values which they previously ----
2413 // followed. The easiest thing to do is to just try to feed SelectionDAG ----
2414 // input it's happy with. ----
2415 // ----
2416 // Map of {Variable x: Fragments y} where the fragments y of variable x have ----
2417 // have at least one non-undef location defined already. Don't use directly, ----
2418 // instead call DefineBits and HasDefinedBits. ----
2419 SmallDenseMap> ----
2420 VarsWithDef; 0
2421 // Specify that V (a fragment of A) has a non-undef location. ----
2422 auto DefineBits = [&VarsWithDef](DebugAggregate A, DebugVariable V) { 0
2423 VarsWithDef[A].insert(V.getFragmentOrDefault()); 0
2424 }; 0
2425 // Return true if a non-undef location has been defined for V (a fragment of ----
2426 // A). Doesn't imply that the location is currently non-undef, just that a ----
2427 // non-undef location has been seen previously. ----
2428 auto HasDefinedBits = [&VarsWithDef](DebugAggregate A, DebugVariable V) { 0
2429 auto FragsIt = VarsWithDef.find(A); 0
2430 if (FragsIt == VarsWithDef.end()) 0
2431 return false; 0
2432 return llvm::any_of(FragsIt->second, [V](auto Frag) { 0
2433 return DIExpression::fragmentsOverlap(Frag, V.getFragmentOrDefault()); 0
2434 }); 0
2435 }; 0
2436 ----
2437 bool Changed = false; 0
2438 DenseMap> VariableMap; 0
2439 ----
2440 // Scan over the entire block, not just over the instructions mapped by ----
2441 // FnVarLocs, because wedges in FnVarLocs may only be seperated by debug ----
2442 // instructions. ----
2443 for (const Instruction &I : *BB) { 0
2444 // Get the defs that come just before this instruction. ----
2445 const auto *Locs = FnVarLocs.getWedge(&I); 0
2446 if (!Locs) 0
2447 continue; 0
2448 ----
2449 NumWedgesScanned++; 0
2450 bool ChangedThisWedge = false; 0
2451 // The new pruned set of defs. ----
2452 SmallVector NewDefs; 0
2453 ----
2454 // Iterate over the existing defs. ----
2455 for (const VarLocInfo &Loc : *Locs) { 0
2456 NumDefsScanned++; 0
2457 DebugAggregate Aggr{FnVarLocs.getVariable(Loc.VariableID).getVariable(), 0
2458 Loc.DL.getInlinedAt()}; 0
2459 DebugVariable Var = FnVarLocs.getVariable(Loc.VariableID); 0
2460 ----
2461 // Remove undef entries that are encountered before any non-undef ----
2462 // intrinsics from the entry block. ----
2463 if (Loc.Values.isKillLocation(Loc.Expr) && !HasDefinedBits(Aggr, Var)) { 0
2464 // Did not insert this Loc, which is the same as removing it. ----
2465 NumDefsRemoved++; 0
2466 ChangedThisWedge = true; 0
2467 continue; 0
2468 } ----
2469 ----
2470 DefineBits(Aggr, Var); 0
2471 NewDefs.push_back(Loc); 0
2472 } ----
2473 ----
2474 // Replace the existing wedge with the pruned version. ----
2475 if (ChangedThisWedge) { 0
2476 FnVarLocs.setWedge(&I, std::move(NewDefs)); 0
2477 NumWedgesChanged++; 0
2478 Changed = true; 0
2479 } ----
2480 } 0
2481 ----
2482 return Changed; 0
2483 } 0

2485 static bool removeRedundantDbgLocs(const BasicBlock *BB, 0
2486 FunctionVarLocsBuilder &FnVarLocs) { ----

2499 static DenseSet findVarsWithStackSlot(Function &Fn) { 0
2500 DenseSet Result; 0
2501 for (auto &BB : Fn) { 0
2502 for (auto &I : BB) { 0
2503 // Any variable linked to an instruction is considered ----
2504 // interesting. Ideally we only need to check Allocas, however, a ----
2505 // DIAssignID might get dropped from an alloca but not stores. In that ----
2506 // case, we need to consider the variable interesting for NFC behaviour ----
2507 // with this change. TODO: Consider only looking at allocas. ----
2508 for (DbgAssignIntrinsic *DAI : at::getAssignmentMarkers(&I)) { 0
2509 Result.insert({DAI->getVariable(), DAI->getDebugLoc().getInlinedAt()}); 0
2510 } ----
2511 } ----
2512 } ----
2513 return Result; 0
2514 } ----

2516 static void analyzeFunction(Function &Fn, const DataLayout &Layout, 0
2517 FunctionVarLocsBuilder *FnVarLocs) { ----
2518 // The analysis will generate location definitions for all variables, but we ----
2519 // only need to perform a dataflow on the set of variables which have a stack ----
2520 // slot. Find those now. ----
2521 DenseSet VarsWithStackSlot = findVarsWithStackSlot(Fn); 0
2522 ----
2523 bool Changed = false; 0
2524 ----
2525 // Use a scope block to clean up AssignmentTrackingLowering before running ----
2526 // MemLocFragmentFill to reduce peak memory consumption. ----
2527 { ----
2528 AssignmentTrackingLowering Pass(Fn, Layout, &VarsWithStackSlot); 0
2529 Changed = Pass.run(FnVarLocs); 0
2530 } 0
2531 ----
2532 if (Changed) { 0
2533 MemLocFragmentFill Pass(Fn, &VarsWithStackSlot, ----
2534 shouldCoalesceFragments(Fn)); 0
2535 Pass.run(FnVarLocs); 0
2536 ----
2537 // Remove redundant entries. As well as reducing memory consumption and ----
2538 // avoiding waiting cycles later by burning some now, this has another ----
2539 // important job. That is to work around some SelectionDAG quirks. See ----
2540 // removeRedundantDbgLocsUsingForwardScan comments for more info on that. ----
2541 for (auto &BB : Fn) 0
2542 removeRedundantDbgLocs(&BB, *FnVarLocs); 0
2543 } 0
2544 } 0

2546 bool AssignmentTrackingAnalysis::runOnFunction(Function &F) { 2 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
2547 if (!isAssignmentTrackingEnabled(*F.getParent())) 2 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
2548 return false; 2 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
2549 ----
2550 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "AssignmentTrackingAnalysis run on " << F.getName() 0
2551 << "\n"); ----
2552 auto DL = std::make_unique(F.getParent()); 0
2553 ----
2554 // Clear previous results. ----
2555 Results->clear(); 0
2556 ----
2557 FunctionVarLocsBuilder Builder; 0
2558 analyzeFunction(F, *DL.get(), &Builder); 0
2559 ----
2560 // Save these results. ----
2561 Results->init(Builder); 0
2562 ----
2563 if (PrintResults && isFunctionInPrintList(F.getName())) 0
2564 Results->print(errs(), F); 0
2565 ----
2566 // Return false because this pass does not modify the function. ----
2567 return false; 0
2568 } 0
